[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ Dear readers, it is a great pleasure to introduce my first Chessable course, which covers the Bogo-Indian Defense for Black!  First of all, let me say a few words about myself… I am a WGM/IM, Romania's #1 ranked and World's #31 ranked women's chess player. I was born in the Republic of Moldova a bit more than 27 years ago, and I started playing chess in the first grade. At 14 years old, I became the youngest ever Women's National Champion. A few years later, I moved to Romania, the country that I've represented since then at five Olympiads, winning an individual bronze in 2014.   I have been an IM since 2013, and I have won a lot of national and international tournaments. I am still very much an active player, and I'm constantly trying to improve! If one had to characterize my playing style, it would probably be described as dynamic, although I've noticed that, with every year that passes by, a certain strategical 'laziness' sneaks in more and more. I'd say that one of my biggest strengths as a player is opening flexibility: I can play almost any opening or line. Thus, I would like to share some of my experiences with you!  While the Bogo-Indian is not the most popular opening on the highest level, many top players still keep it in their repertoire @@StartBracket@@e.g., GM Vitiugov, GM Le Quang, GM Ju Wenjun@@EndBracket@@. As in many Indian structures  (where one doesn't immediately occupy the center with a pawn)  ,  this opening's greatest advantage is the flexible pawn structures one gets. This fact helps the better player to outplay their opponent, as they can choose the pawn structure they go for, depending on the opponent's strengths and weaknesses.   I used to play The Bogo-Indian when I was still a junior and then somehow forgot about it, replacing it with its 'older sister' - the Queen's Indian. The knowledge and experience I gained from my 'Bogo-Indian days' helped me to understand the latter, which has a lot more theory to memorize and structures to study. Later on, I completed my repertoire by adding the King's Indian to it. If you're at the beginning of building a repertoire for Black against 1.d4, or if you want to get initiated in the Indian structures, I recommend that you start with the Bogo-Indian. You will learn many typical ideas in the resulting structures, and you'll also learn how to think schematically - a very valuable skill!   Another reason why I like the Bogo-Indian is the small volume of variations to memorize. Very rarely will you need to remember everything move by move. One needs to understand the ideas of the opening, and that was my focus in the course. Hence, why I often draw your attention to the principles one needs to follow. Once you understand the ideas, you'll see that the good moves will start coming to you naturally! This is my approach to openings: I like to structure everything based on schematic thinking and ideas rather than just memorizing everything like a computer. I find it to be much more effective! After all, one needs to learn how to study chess, not how to use an engine, right? I hope this course will also give you the necessary tips and skills to work on the openings by yourself. This is something that takes a long time to master, so be patient with yourself.  When I started working on the course, I had my doubts. I remembered that ten years ago - when I was playing the Bogo-Indian myself - there were certain lines in which I struggled to find equality, especially when playing against well-prepared, higher-rated opponents. To my surprise, almost all of these problems have been solved in the meantime! The chess theory is restless, and so are the engines. Since the time GM Efim Bogoljubov  (1889-1952)  started playing this opening, things have changed and evolved significantly. You can check the Model Games database to convince yourself of this.   There was only one line where, for a long time, I struggled to find good, healthy play for Black: in a sideline of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  Bb4  4.Bd2  . I am very proud to have found a really interesting new idea there!  In conclusion, I am very happy to have rediscovered the Bogo-Indian, and I can't wait to use it again in my future tournaments. I hope you will share my enthusiasm and enjoy your journey through the course. }
*

