[Black "4.Nc3 b6 5.Bd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops White's e4-ideas. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. Bd2
{ One more way of making sure there will be no doubled pawns on the c-file. }
5... Bb7 6. e3 Bxc3
{ The idea is that, even if White has the bishop pair and no doubled pawns, the bishop on c3 will not be ideally placed, especially after Ne4. After that move, we'll either get the bishop back, or it will be forced to go to a worse position. }
7. Bxc3 Ne4 8. Rc1 O-O
{ We don't have to hurry with taking on c3, as  9.Bb4  is not dangerous thanks to  9...c5  . }
9. Bd3 f5 10. O-O
{ White finished their development and might consider the option of 'saving' their bishop with 11. Be1. One might think it's now time to take on c3, but that would be a mistake!   After  10...Nxc3  11.Rxc3  we don't have time to get control over e4 @@StartBracket@@d6, Nd7, Nf6 takes too long@@EndBracket@@ and White will just play Re1 and e4 with an advantage. }
10... d6
{ We continue our development and prepare c5 to stop White's pawn expansion on the queenside.   Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
