1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops White's e4-ideas. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. e3
{ White allows Black to double the c-pawns. In return, they want to gain space in the center after Bd3 and e4.   The problem with  5...Bxc3  is that we won't have enough counterplay for the space we're giving up. The c4-pawn will be well defended by the bishop on d3 and later by the knight on d2 as well. That's why we choose a different plan here. }
5... Bb7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O d5
{ Going for a central strategy and stopping White's e4 for good! } 8. cxd5 exd5
{ Taking on d5 with the knight wouldn't be good, as it loses control over the e4-square and leaves too few pieces protecting our kingside. White has two plans now. One: start an attack on the kingside with Ne5, f4, Qf3;  and two: start an expansion on the queenside with a3, b4. }
9. a3 Bd6 10. b4 { This plan is mainly aimed at Black's c5. } 10... Nbd7
{ Now we can develop our knight to d7, as there is no Ne5 any longer. } 11. Qb3
{ White wants to play b5, fixing the potentially weak pawn on c7. Why allow it? }
11... c6
{ 11...a6  wouldn't solve the problem, as White can renew their threat with  12.a4  . }
12. e4
{ White tries to make use of the fact that the bishop on b7 doesn't control e4 any longer. }
12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 h6
{ After a series of exchanges, we need to cover g5, so we don't have to worry about any Ng5 or Bg5. We then plan to play Nf6, forcing the white bishop to move, followed by a5 to create some counterplay.  Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
