1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops White's e4-ideas. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. Bg5
{ A rare case when White's dark-squared bishop does not develop to b2. The downside of this move is that Black hasn't castled yet, so ideas with h6, g5 and Ne4 are possible. }
5... h6
{ It's always useful to ask this bishop a question: Do you want to take on f6 or not? }
6. Bh4 { The most natural move. } 6... Bb7 { Stopping e4 once again. } 7. Nd2
e5 { An interesting pawn sacrifice! } 8. dxe5 Bxc3
{ An important intermediate move, spoiling White's pawn structure. If  9.exf6  , Black has  9...Bxf6  . }
9. bxc3 g5 10. Bg3 { White's bishop cannot really avoid being traded. } 10...
Nh5 11. e3
{ 11.e4  is possible too, although I find it to be slightly worse because this pawn might become a target, so White's knight will have to stick to protecting it. }
11... Nxg3 12. hxg3 Qe7
{ Black wants to either get the pawn back, or force White to weaken the pawn structure. }
13. f4
{ The only way of protecting e5.  13.Nf3  wouldn't be a permanent solution, as after  13...Na6  followed by O-O-O, g4 would be a very unpleasant threat. }
13... Na6
{ White has serious issues with finishing their development: The bishop must stay on f1 from where it protects the g2-pawn and castling long is risky due to the compromised pawn structure on the queenside... Meanwhile, Black will castle long on the next move and then try to open up the centre with either f6 or d6. I'd say Black has more than enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
