1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Nbd2
{ A move preferred by many strong GMs: Carlsen, Kramnik, Ding Liren, Giri... White wants to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board, trying to win the bishop pair after an eventual a3-Bxd2. Then it will be much easier for White to start their play on the queenside, as the dark-squared bishop supports the pawn expansion much better than a knight.   At the same time, White wants to achieve that without allowing Black to double the c-pawns, like in the lines with  4.Nc3  . }
4... b6 { First step: finishing the development! } 5. e3
{ A quiet setup. White wants to finish the development on the kingside, then fianchetto the bishop to b2 and prepare e4. }
5... Bb7 6. Bd3
{ The optimal placement for the bishop, as it supports the e4-plan. } 6... O-O
7. O-O d5 { Once again, fighting for the center and preventing e4. } 8. a3 Be7
{ We retreat to e7 rather than d6 because if White plays b4, we don't want the c5-threat to come with a tempo. }
9. b4 { White is now ready to play c5. } 9... c5
{ The best way to stop White's c5. } 10. bxc5 bxc5 11. Rb1
{ A move tried by Kramnik in 2018 against Martinez. } 11... Ba6
{ Same reaction as in the variation with White's bishop on e2. } 12. Ne5 Qc8
{ We cover the c6-square so that White can't play Nc6 after we finish our development with Nbd7. At the same time, the queen defends the bishop on a6 just in case. Simplifications in the center will follow. }
