[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.Nbd2 b6 5.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Nbd2
{ A move preferred by many strong GMs: Carlsen, Kramnik, Ding Liren, Giri... White wants to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board, trying to win the bishop pair after an eventual a3-Bxd2. Then it will be much easier for White to start their play on the queenside, as the dark-squared bishop supports the pawn expansion much better than a knight.   At the same time, White wants to achieve that without allowing Black to double the c-pawns, like in the lines with  4.Nc3  . }
4... b6 { First step: finishing the development! } 5. a3
{ White wants us to decide as soon as possible what we're doing about our bishop on b4. There's no other choice than taking on d2 because e4 would follow otherwise @@StartBracket@@for example  5...Be7  6.e4  @@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2
{ If White captures with the bishop, we go for the plan with d6 and e5. We have enough time for that. }
6... Bb7 7. e3
{ This setup allows our b7-bishop to be 'the master of the long diagonal'. This means we can go for our d6/e5-plan without any worries. }
7... d6 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. O-O
{ If  9.Qc2  , not allowing us to play Ne4 anymore, then  9...c5  followed by  10... Rc8, x-raying White's queen and preparing to castle. Then we play d5, either immediately or after taking on d4. }
9... O-O 10. b4 { White stays true to their queenside expansion. } 10... e5
{ So we also stay true to our d6/e5-idea, which we might follow up with an attack on the kingside thanks to our super strong b7-bishop!  Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.Nbd2 b6 5.a3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Nbd2
{ A move preferred by many strong GMs: Carlsen, Kramnik, Ding Liren, Giri... White wants to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board, trying to win the bishop pair after an eventual a3-Bxd2. Then it will be much easier for White to start their play on the queenside, as the dark-squared bishop supports the pawn expansion much better than a knight.   At the same time, White wants to achieve that without allowing Black to double the c-pawns, like in the lines with  4.Nc3  . }
4... b6 { First step: finishing the development! } 5. a3
{ White wants us to decide as soon as possible what we're doing about our bishop on b4. There's no other choice than taking on d2 because e4 would follow otherwise @@StartBracket@@for example  5...Be7  6.e4  @@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2
{ If White captures with the bishop, we go for the plan with d6 and e5. We have enough time for that. }
6... Bb7 7. Bg5
{ This move can't be good. We know that we must develop in the opening phase, rather than move the same piece several times. Surprisingly, this move has been played quite a few times - it's actually the most popular one! }
7... d6 { Our all-time favorite move in our Bogo approach! } 8. e3 h6
{ It's useful to ask the g5-bishop an existential question: Why are you going to h4? Or do you want to trade on f6? }
9. Bh4 Nbd7 { Continuing our development and setting up a nice trap. } 10. Be2
{ This falls straight into our trap! } 10... g5 11. Bg3 h5
{ Threatening to win that g3-bishop.  12.h4  runs into  12...g4  and the pawn on g2 will fall. }
12. h3 Ne4
{ With a better position for Black. If the bishop retreats with  13.Bh2  , we can play  13...g4!  .   
Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
