1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Nbd2
{ A move preferred by many strong GMs: Carlsen, Kramnik, Ding Liren, Giri... White wants to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board, trying to win the bishop pair after an eventual a3-Bxd2. Then it will be much easier for White to start their play on the queenside, as the dark-squared bishop supports the pawn expansion much better than a knight.   At the same time, White wants to achieve that without allowing Black to double the c-pawns, like in the lines with  4.Nc3  . }
4... b6 { First step: finishing the development! } 5. a3
{ White wants us to decide as soon as possible what we're doing about our bishop on b4. There's no other choice than taking on d2 because e4 would follow otherwise @@StartBracket@@for example  5...Be7  6.e4  @@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7
{ As is usual in this structure, White has to decide where to develop their light-squared bishop: to g2, or to e2/d3. An extra option here is to start with the pawn expansion on the queenside. }
7. e3
{ If White chooses to finish their development before starting the pawn expansion on the queenside, Black will have just enough time to organize something in the center. }
7... O-O 8. Be2 d5
{ If White castles now, we'll just take on c4 and claim to have a good position, as White moved their bishop twice @@StartBracket@@Be2, Bxc4@@EndBracket@@. We should follow up by preparing c5. }
9. b3 { Getting ready to take on c4 with the pawn. } 9... Nbd7
{ Finishing the development and preparing c5. } 10. O-O c5
{ We will follow up with a central strategy: Rc8, Ne4, Qe7 and then, at the right moment, we take off some pressure in the center with either cxd4 or dxc4.  Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
