[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.Bd2 Qe7 5.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Bd2 Qe7
{ Defending the bishop and setting up a little trap.   White can't capture with  5.Bxb4  , as after  5...Qxb4+  , Black either wins the b2-pawn or the c4-pawn.  An additional idea that arises after this move is to capture on d2. If White recaptures with the queen, Black can continue with Ne4 in some lines and the white queen has to leave the a5-e1-diagonal, after which Black's Qb4+ might be unpleasant once again. }
5. Nc3
{ White's idea is to get a position with the bishop pair @@StartBracket@@Black will eventually have to take on c3@@EndBracket@@ and then open up the position for them. We can therefore deduce that Black should either try to keep the position closed, or eliminate one of White's bishops. This line reminds us a bit of the Nimzo. }
5... b6 6. e3
{ This is the most straightforward setup for White, in which they calmly develop the kingside and then prepare e4. On the other hand, it allows the bishop on b7 to reign over the long diagonal. Our plan will keep this in mind. }
6... Bb7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O d6
{ Black delays capturing the knight on c3 until White spends a tempo with a3. At the same time, we continue our development with Nbd7. Then we can either play e5 @@StartBracket@@a solid plan@@EndBracket@@ or take on c3, followed by Ne4 and f5, starting a typical attack on the kingside @@StartBracket@@a more ambitious plan@@EndBracket@@. We should remember to keep control over the e4-square, not allowing White to play e4 themselves. When they are ready to do so, Black should be able to take on c3 and play Ne4. }
9. a3 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Ne4
{ This position perfectly illustrates the downside of White having developed the bishop to d3 rather than fianchettoing it, as the b7-bishop is unchallenged on the long diagonal  (unlike with the bishop on g2)  , and as a result, White's king might later face an unpleasant attack.  Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
*

