[Black "4.Bd2 Qe7 5.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Bd2 Qe7
{ Defending the bishop and setting up a little trap.   White can't capture with  5.Bxb4  , as after  5...Qxb4+  , Black either wins the b2-pawn or the c4-pawn.  An additional idea that arises after this move is to capture on d2. If White recaptures with the queen, Black can continue with Ne4 in some lines and the white queen has to leave the a5-e1-diagonal, after which Black's Qb4+ might be unpleasant once again. }
5. a3
{ White tries to force the matter. a3 is a useful move, as it covers the b4-square @@StartBracket@@no more Qb4+ threats@@EndBracket@@ and prepares White's pawn expansion on the queenside @@StartBracket@@with b4@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bxd2+
{ Black's plan will be similar after all of the captures. We'll play d6, then e5, and, depending on what White will do about their pawn structure in the center, we'll choose our plan accordingly. }
6. Nbxd2
{ The mainline, though it looks to me that the knight is not as happy on d2 as it would be on c3, from where it would not only control e4 but also d5. }
6... d6
{ White has a few options here, though all of them will be met by the same reaction: short castle followed by e5. We already have a feel of this pawn structure and now we'll see the possible plans. }
7. e4 e5
{ Once again, White faces a choice on how to handle the pawn structure in the center. They can close it with d5, take on e5 or wait a bit by defending the e4-pawn. }
8. d5 a5
{ As the knight is placed on d2 rather than on c3, Black threatens to play a4, making it impossible for White to make any progress on the queenside. Another positive aspect of our a4-threat is that it would secure the very nice c5-square for our b8-knight. }
9. b4 { Not allowing a4 and trying to make c5 happen as fast as possible! }
9... O-O 10. Bd3 Nh5
{ Our strategy is simple here. We want to force White to weaken their kingside by playing g3 and then start our counterplay on the kingside.   After  11.g3  Bh3  White's king is stuck in the center and we follow up with g6 and f5.  Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
