[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.Bd2 Qe7 5.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Bd2 Qe7
{ Defending the bishop and setting up a little trap.   White can't capture with  5.Bxb4  , as after  5...Qxb4+  , Black either wins the b2-pawn or the c4-pawn.  An additional idea that arises after this move is to capture on d2. If White recaptures with the queen, Black can continue with Ne4 in some lines and the white queen has to leave the a5-e1-diagonal, after which Black's Qb4+ might be unpleasant once again. }
5. g3 { The main move. } 5... Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2
{ This is not where the knight wanted to end up - it would prefer to be on c3, from where it would not only support the e4-move but also control the d5-square! Now we can play the 'old' setup with d6 and e5. }
6... d6 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O e5 9. e4 a5
{ An important move that stops a possible pawn expansion on the queenside after White closes the center with d5. It also secures us a nice place for the b8-knight on c5, like in the best King's Indian tradition! }
10. Qc2 Nc6
{ This move forces White to take the pressure off in the center. Taking on e5 is never a good idea, as that will leave White with a weak d4-square, so the best option is to close up the center with d5. }
11. d5 Nb8
{ Now our knight is heading towards the best spot it has on the board - the c5-square! We play the knight to b8 rather than to b4 @@StartBracket@@with an attack on the white queen@@EndBracket@@ because we want to keep two possible routes for our knight @@StartBracket@@a6-c5 and d7-c5@@EndBracket@@.   If after  11...Nb4  White plays  12.Qc3  , Black can't play  12...Na6  because the a5-pawn is hanging.   If White tries the same after  11...Nb8  12.Qc3  , we can play  12...Nd7  and go to c5 from there.  Chessable note: You can find thefull variation here. }
