[Black "4.Bd2 Qe7 5.g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Bd2 Qe7
{ Defending the bishop and setting up a little trap.   White can't capture with  5.Bxb4  , as after  5...Qxb4+  , Black either wins the b2-pawn or the c4-pawn.  An additional idea that arises after this move is to capture on d2. If White recaptures with the queen, Black can continue with Ne4 in some lines and the white queen has to leave the a5-e1-diagonal, after which Black's Qb4+ might be unpleasant once again. }
5. g3 { The main move. } 5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nc6
{ An interesting move which has become very fashionable lately. It feels a bit strange to develop the knight in front of the c7-pawn, but it has its purpose: to take the e5-square away from the knight on f3! We also threaten Ne4 followed by Qb4+, so White should do something about it. }
7. b3
{ White defends the pawn on c4 so that they don't have to worry about it after our Ne4 and Qb4+. This move also consolidates the center: After d5 and dxc4, White can take back with the b-pawn, creating a very nice center for themselves. This is actually one of the most unpleasant moves for us, as our knight on c6 will not be exactly comfortable here and we'll have some difficulties in our fight for the center. }
7... a5
{ That's why I want to suggest this interesting move, which according to my database has been played only once, although with a different idea from the one I'm proposing: an attack on the a2-b3-c4 pawn chain with a5-a4! }
8. Nc3 a4
{ An interesting pawn sacrifice! White has to choose between spoiling their pawn structure @@StartBracket@@if taking on a4 with the pawn@@EndBracket@@ and giving up control over the e4- and b5-squares @@StartBracket@@if capturing with the knight@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Nxa4 Ne4 10. Qd3 Qb4+ { A forced sequence heading towards an endgame. } 11.
Nd2 { Only good move. } 11... Nxd2 12. Qxd2 Nxd4
{ Threatening Nc2 with a fork. } 13. Qxb4 Nc2+ 14. Kd2 Nxb4
{ We will need to solve the problem of the c8-bishop by playing Nc6 again, then d6, Kd7 @@StartBracket@@defending the c6-knight@@EndBracket@@, b6, Bb7 and exchanging the light-squared bishops.  Chessable note: You can find thefull variations starting from here. }
