1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Bd2 Qe7
{ Defending the bishop and setting up a little trap.   White can't capture with  5.Bxb4  , as after  5...Qxb4+  , Black either wins the b2-pawn or the c4-pawn.  An additional idea that arises after this move is to capture on d2. If White recaptures with the queen, Black can continue with Ne4 in some lines and the white queen has to leave the a5-e1-diagonal, after which Black's Qb4+ might be unpleasant once again. }
5. g3 { The main move. } 5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nc6
{ An interesting move which has become very fashionable lately. It feels a bit strange to develop the knight in front of the c7-pawn, but it has its purpose: to take the e5-square away from the knight on f3! We also threaten Ne4 followed by Qb4+, so White should do something about it. }
7. Nc3 d5
{ White has a few possibilities here:   7.cxd5  claiming that they have an advantage due to our strangely placed knight on  c6  in a Carlsbad structure.   7.Ne5  , forcing Black to take with  7...dxc4  , then take on  8.Nxc6  , and continue by playing against our spoiled pawn structure.   Play  7.Bg2  to continue the development, allowing us to take on  7...dxc4  but gaining space in the center in return, and thus attempt to claim the advantage due to our difficulties in finishing our development on the queenside. }
8. Bg2 dxc4 9. O-O { The only way for White to play for an advantage! } 9...
O-O 10. Ne5
{ We intended to play Rd8 followed by e5, that's why White plays Ne5 themselves. }
10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7
{ White must defend their e5-pawn. It gives us enough time to organize some counterplay. }
12. Qd4 Qc5
{ Exchanging the queens is almost always a relief in a position with little space. White cannot avoid it, as the pawn on e5 will fall otherwise. }
13. Qxc5 Nxc5
{ White has good compensation for the sacrificed pawn, as the bishop on g2 is a monster and we will have some difficulties finishing the development on the queenside. Black must be very precise here to avoid getting in trouble.  14.Rfc1  will transpose to the mainline after  14...Rb8  15.Nb5  Bd7  . }
14. Nb5
{ White plays this move not only to attack c7 but also to stop us from defending the c4-pawn with a6, Rb8 and b5. }
14... Rb8
{ An invitation for White to take some poisoned pawns!  15.Nxa7  will be met by  15...c6  and the knight is trapped. If  15.Nxc7  then  15...Bd7  and the knight is stuck again.  Our plan is to continue with 15... Bd7, when either the knight will have to move, or many simplifications will follow.  Chessable note: You can find thefull variations starting from here. }
