[Black "4.Nc3 b6  5.g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops any e4-ideas White might have. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. g3
{ It looks to me as if this plan combines the Catalan with the Nimzo. I think it's a risky setup for White, as it allows Bxc3, doubling the c-pawns and gaining a long-term strategical advantage. On the other hand, White will try to gain as much space in the center as possible, and then start an attack on the kingside. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Bb7
{ For now, we just continue to develop our pieces. It's very hard to make a mistake if we follow the basic chess principles: develop our pieces, bring our king to safety, fight for the center, occupy the open files, etc. ... }
7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O
{ Both sides have almost finished their development. Black now faces a choice: where to place our b8-knight? On d7 or on c6? Ideally, it should go to c6 and then to a5, from where it attacks the doubled pawns.   However, if we play  8...Nc6  right away, White might answer with  9.Ne5  . That's why we don't hurry and go for  8... d6 instead. }
8... d6 9. a4
{ White wants to play a5. The main purpose of this move is to take the a5-square away from our knight. We can't allow that! }
9... Nc6 10. Nd2
{ White is now ready to play e4. As there's no way of stopping it, we should prepare a way to meet it. }
10... Na5 11. e4
{ As said before, piece exchanges are not convenient for White, as they want to keep as many resources as possible for their attack on the kingside. }
11... c5
{ 11...e5  would not be a good idea here for several reasons. Firstly, after  12.d5  our bishop on b7 becomes a bad piece @@StartBracket@@we usually only play e5 after an exchange of the light-squared bishops@@EndBracket@@.  Secondly, White might then attack our pawn chain with f4 and, if we answer with Nd7, they can even play f5 with the idea of g4, g5, etc. ... This position would be a nightmare for Black, as there wouldn't be any counterplay left. Furthermore, there wouldn't be enough space for Black's pieces to maneuver around. Black should avoid this type of position at all costs! }
12. f4 { White is gaining as much space as they can. } 12... cxd4
{ A move which might look strange at first glance, as we undouble White's pawns. However, we also open up the c-file for ourselves! This will ensure us enough counterplay. }
13. cxd4 Rc8
{ White has serious trouble defending the c4-pawn. We can increase the pressure on it with Ba6 and Qc7, if needed. Black's position is preferable, as White's attack is too slow. }
