1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops any e4-ideas White might have. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. Bd2
{ One more way of making sure there will be no doubled pawns on the c-file. }
5... Bb7 6. e3 Bxc3
{ The idea is that, even if White has the bishop pair and no doubled pawns, the bishop on c3 will not be ideally placed, especially after Ne4. After that move, we'll either get the bishop back, or it will be forced to go to a worse position. }
7. Bxc3 Ne4 8. Bb4 { Keeping the bishop pair. } 8... c5
{ We force the bishop to retreat to a3. } 9. Ba3 O-O 10. Be2
{ Finishing the development. } 10... d6
{ A very nice pawn construction that limits the a3-bishop. } 11. O-O f5
{ And now we're back to the plan of a kingside attack! The knight on e4 is doing a fine job stopping any counterplay in the center, so we can calmly build up our attack. }
12. Nd2 Qg5
{ Creating very unpleasant pressure on g2.   If White trades the knight with  13.Nxe4  , we just play  13...Bxe4  , and after  14.Bf3  , we develop our knight  14...Nc6  .  The position would be balanced, as White's bishop on a3 will need a lot of time to re-enter the game @@StartBracket@@with b3, Bb2 maybe@@EndBracket@@, while we can just continue to increase the pressure on the kingside with Rf6-Rh@@StartBracket@@g@@EndBracket@@6. }
13. Bf3 Na6
{ The knight can no longer develop to c6, as e4 would be hanging, so we bring it to a6 where it defends c5. Next, we can prepare Rf6-g@@StartBracket@@h@@EndBracket@@6 or even d5. }
