1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops any e4-ideas White might have. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. Qc2 { Another way of avoiding the doubled pawn structure. } 5... Bb7 6. e3
{ White allows us to spoil their pawn structure on the kingside, but they hope to get some counterplay by making use of the open g-file. }
6... O-O { Bringing the king to safety first. } 7. Bd3 c5
{ And now, as White was ready to play 8. e4, we are first to strike in the center! }
8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3
{ White allows a somewhat funny structure with two pairs of doubled pawns, but they get the bishop pair in return. }
9... Bxf3 10. gxf3
{ Now White has two bishops against two knights, but can we call this an open position? I believe that the two knights are better in this case, as the position has a rather closed character. }
10... Nc6
{ The usual setup. We plan to follow up with Rc8 and Na5, applying some pressure on the c4-pawn. }
11. d5
{ White wants to open up the position at any cost! The d5-pawn is untouchable anyway, as h7 would be left unprotected in case we go for it. }
11... Na5
{ As Black has the pair of knights, they have to keep the position closed! }
12. e4 Nh5
{ The knights are placed a bit strangely, but they are doing a good job! We want to close the center with e5, which would get us great control over the dark squares. The plan would be simple then: play Nf4, g6 and h5 to seal the kingside. Based on which side White's king chooses to go, we then decide on which side of the board we want to counterattack. }
