{ Forcing White's rook away from its active position on d4 and freeing the e6-square for a possible rerouting of the d7-knight via c5, or for our queen which would attack c4 from there. }
15. Rdd1 h6
{ The bishop is once again asked a question. If it takes on f6, we can go for the d5-plan, as White no longer has the bishop pair. If it retreats to h4, we play 16... Qe6, attacking the c4-pawn and getting rid of the pin. }
