1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops any e4-ideas White might have. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. Qc2 { Another way of avoiding the doubled pawn structure. } 5... Bb7 6. a3
{ We don't have time to retreat to e7, as White is ready to play e4.   6.Bg5  would be similar to the  5. Bg5 line. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 O-O
{ White has the bishop pair, but it came with quite a high price: Black is much ahead in development! }
8. e3 d5
{ A central strategy. The best way to take advantage of our faster development is to organize some play in the center. }
9. b3 Nbd7 { The development is now complete for us! } 10. Be2 c5
{ With the idea of playing Rc8, making the queen on c3 uncomfortable. } 11. O-O
Rc8 12. Bb2 { White has finally completed the development as well. } 12... dxc4
{ A series of simplifications in the center will follow. Our last move will highlight the unpleasant x-ray on White's queen. }
13. Bxc4
{ By recapturing with the bishop, White loses a tempo @@StartBracket@@the bishop moved twice in order to take on c4@@EndBracket@@ and faces an unpleasant x-ray on the c-file. }
13... Ne4 { Destroying White's battery on the long dark diagonal. } 14. Qd3 Qe7
{ Planning 15... Rfd8, after which Black can either go for several simplifications in the center or even get ambitious and start an attack on the kingside with Ng5, making use of the 'monster' on b7. }
