[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. The Nimzo line 4. Nc3"]
[Black "5.e3 with 8.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops any e4-ideas White might have. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. e3
{ White allows Black to double the c-pawns. In return, they want to gain space in the center after Bd3 and e4.   The problem with  5...Bxc3  is that we won't have enough counterplay for the space we're giving up. The c4-pawn will be well defended by the bishop on d3 and later by the knight on d2 as well. That's why we choose a different plan here. }
5... Bb7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O d5
{ Going for a central strategy and stopping White's e4 for good! } 8. a3 Bxc3
{ Retreating to d6 is also possible but I prefer this type of structure, as it's very easy to play with Black. }
9. bxc3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 c5
{ Black has given up the bishop pair but White's c1-bishop can hardly be called a good piece with almost all of White's pawns on dark squares. As for our plan, we have to attack White's pawn chain. The easiest way to achieve that is by preparing e5. }
11. Bb2 Qc7 { A small x-ray. The threat is cxd4. } 12. Qe2 Nc6
{ We developed our last piece and, at the same time, we're ready to attack the center with e5. }
13. Bd3 e5 14. e4
{ What follows is a forced sequence. What can we do? Sometimes we have to make an effort to remember a long variation. It's worth the effort though, as Black equalizes comfortably. }
14... cxd4 15. cxd4 exd4 16. Nxd4
{ White claims that in an open position the bishop pair will assure them a pleasant advantage. }
16... Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Rad8
{ We're not afraid of spoiling our pawn structure and opening up the king with  18.Bxf6  gxf6  , as there are not enough pieces left on the board for White to create a dangerous attack. A the same time, the doubled f-pawns will hold in White's pawn majority on the kingside very nicely in all endgames.   If White tries to keep the bishop pair with  18.Bb2  , we start an attack on the e4-pawn with  18...Qf4  followed by Rfe8. The position is balanced. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. The Nimzo line 4. Nc3"]
[Black "5.e3  with 8.a3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops any e4-ideas White might have. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. e3
{ White allows Black to double the c-pawns. In return, they want to gain space in the center after Bd3 and e4.   The problem with  5...Bxc3  is that we won't have enough counterplay for the space we're giving up. The c4-pawn will be well defended by the bishop on d3 and later by the knight on d2 as well. That's why we choose a different plan here. }
5... Bb7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O d5
{ Going for a central strategy and stopping White's e4 for good! } 8. a3 Bxc3
{ Retreating to d6 is also possible but I prefer this type of structure, as it's very easy to play with Black. }
9. bxc3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 c5
{ Black has given up the bishop pair but White's c1-bishop can hardly be called a good piece with almost all of White's pawns on dark squares. As for our plan, we have to attack White's pawn chain. The easiest way to achieve that is by preparing e5. }
11. Bb2 Qc7 { A small x-ray. The threat is cxd4. } 12. Qe2 Nc6
{ We developed our last piece and, at the same time, we're ready to attack the center with e5. }
13. Bd3 e5 14. e4
{ What follows is a forced sequence. What can we do? Sometimes we have to make an effort to remember a long variation. It's worth the effort though, as Black equalizes comfortably. }
14... cxd4 15. cxd4 exd4 16. e5
{ A principled continuation. Black's king is in danger! } 16... Nh5
{ 16...Nd5  loses to  17.Qe4  , with a double attack on h7 and d5. } 17. Qe4 g6
{ We've put a stop to the unpleasant threats created by White's battery on the b1/h7-diagonal. Our h5-knight plans to come back into the game via g7, then either to f5 or e6. }
18. Rac1 { An unpleasant pin. White now wants to take on d4 with the knight. }
18... Qd7 19. Bb5
{ And yet another pin! If it wasn't for Black's next move, we'd be in big trouble... }
19... Ne7 { A fantastic resource that solves all of Black's problems! } 20.
Bxd7 Bxe4 21. Nxd4 Nf4
{ Putting some serious pressure on g2, while also covering the e6-square. } 22.
f3 Bf5
{ The last important move.  22...Bd5  would be too slow and, after  23.Rc7  , White would have a serious advantage. We need to exchange a few more pieces and we already know that doubling the f-pawns is a small price to pay. }
23. Nxf5 Nxf5
{ With a balanced position. White still has the bishop pair, but we have enough good squares for our knights @@StartBracket@@f5 and e6@@EndBracket@@.   If White plays  24.Bxf5  , we take back with  24...gxf5  and then the knight will go to e6, nicely covering c7. The f5-pawn is untouchable.   If instead, White tries  24.Rc7  we can go for  24...Ng7  with the idea of bringing one of our knights to e6 and force the rook to leave the 7th rank. }
