16... Rc8
{ With preferable chances for Black. The position reminds us of a Semi Tarrasch. We have a good version of it, with Black having managed to trade not only one, but two pairs of minor pieces, which significantly lowers the chances of a successful attack on the kingside by White.   Meanwhile, Black can trade a pair of rooks on the c-file, then play Qa8, attacking e4 and trying to force White to play e5, which will leave the d4-pawn vulnerable and the d5-square weak, while also opening the long diagonal for Black's bishop. If White protects the e4-pawn with Re1, then Black can bring the rook to c8, with full control over the c-file. }
