9. bxc3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 c5 11. Re1
{ Another way of preparing e4. The difference is that it also clears the f1-square for the bishop. It might want to retreat there in some cases. }
11... Qc7 { X-raying the bishop. } 12. Bd3 { White is ready to play e4. } 12...
Be4
{ If we can stop White from making e4 happen, we definitely should!  13.Bxe4  isn't good for White, as  13...Nxe4  takes back with a tempo @@StartBracket@@attacking the c3-pawn@@EndBracket@@. Even if White then succeeds in playing e4, it will cost them too many trades, so that the kingside attack won't be dangerous at all. }
13. Bf1 Rd8 { X-raying the queen and preparing Nc6 followed by e5. } 14. Nd2
{ Covering against the x-ray and chasing our bishop away from its very active position. }
14... Bb7 15. Bb2 { Protecting d4, so that e4 becomes a threat once again. }
15... Nc6
{ Keeping the pressure on d4, so that White won't be able to play e4 without sacrificing a pawn. At the same time, Black finished the development and is now ready to attack White's pawn chain once more with e5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. The Nimzo line 4. Nc3"]
[Black "5.e3 with 8.Bd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops any e4-ideas White might have. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. e3
{ White allows Black to double the c-pawns. In return, they want to gain space in the center after Bd3 and e4.   The problem with  5...Bxc3  is that we won't have enough counterplay for the space we're giving up. The c4-pawn will be well defended by the bishop on d3 and later by the knight on d2 as well. That's why we choose a different plan here. }
5... Bb7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O d5
{ Going for a central strategy and stopping White's e4 for good! } 8. Bd2
{ Preparing 9. a3 so that after 9... Bxc3, White can recapture with the bishop. }
8... dxc4
{ But here, we once again force White to lose a tempo, as their light-squared bishop moved twice to land on c4. }
9. Bxc4 Nbd7 { Finishing the development and preparing c5. } 10. Qe2 c5
{ Once again, Black wants to simplify the position. } 11. a3
{ Forcing us to part with the dark-squared bishop. } 11... Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Ne4
{ But we're getting White's in return!  13.Be1  makes no sense because White's rook on f1 would be stuck. }
13. Rac1 Nxc3
{ A series of forced moves that leads to an isolated pawn structure. } 14. Rxc3
Bxf3 15. Qxf3 cxd4 16. exd4 Nf6
{ White's only chance not to get worse will be to play d5 and exchange everything, leading to a completely equal rook endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. The Nimzo line 4. Nc3"]
[Black "5.e3 with 8.cxd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops any e4-ideas White might have. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. e3
{ White allows Black to double the c-pawns. In return, they want to gain space in the center after Bd3 and e4.   The problem with  5...Bxc3  is that we won't have enough counterplay for the space we're giving up. The c4-pawn will be well defended by the bishop on d3 and later by the knight on d2 as well. That's why we choose a different plan here. }
5... Bb7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O d5
{ Going for a central strategy and stopping White's e4 for good! } 8. cxd5 exd5
{ Taking on d5 with the knight wouldn't be good, as it loses control over the e4-square and leaves too few pieces protecting our kingside. White has two plans now. One: start an attack on the kingside with Ne5, f4, Qf3;  and two: start an expansion on the queenside with a3, b4. }
9. Ne5 { Starting an attack on the kingside right away. } 9... Bd6
{ Our plan here is similar to the one in the 9. Bd2-line: we prepare c5 and Nc6. }
10. f4 c5 11. g4
{ An interesting move. Black doesn't have time for  11...Nc6  now, as, after  12.g5  , the pawn on d5 will be left without protection. }
11... Na6
{ But we have another route for our knight!  12.g5  can now be met by  12...Ne4! }
12. Qf3 { Covering e4 and planning 13. g5. } 12... Rb8
{ A nice little move. It protects the b7-bishop so that White doesn't have any ideas with Nc4, either immediately or after we play c4 ourselves. }
13. g5 Bxe5
{ An important intermediate move, designed to weaken g5 in case White takes back with the f-pawn. }
14. fxe5 { 14.dxe5  would run into  14...d4  . } 14... Ne4
{ Attacking g5. If White defends the pawn with  15.h4  , we can continue with  15...Qd7  and Rfd8. Even if we lose pawn after all the captures on e4, we'd have more than enough compensation due to the pressure on d4, the vulnerable white king, and the as-yet undeveloped pieces on c1 and a1. }
