[White "1. The Nimzo line 4. Nc3"]
[Black "5.e3 with 8.cxd5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops any e4-ideas White might have. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. e3
{ White allows Black to double the c-pawns. In return, they want to gain space in the center after Bd3 and e4.   The problem with  5...Bxc3  is that we won't have enough counterplay for the space we're giving up. The c4-pawn will be well defended by the bishop on d3 and later by the knight on d2 as well. That's why we choose a different plan here. }
5... Bb7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O d5
{ Going for a central strategy and stopping White's e4 for good! } 8. cxd5 exd5
{ Taking on d5 with the knight wouldn't be good, as it loses control over the e4-square and leaves too few pieces protecting our kingside. White has two plans now. One: start an attack on the kingside with Ne5, f4, Qf3;  and two: start an expansion on the queenside with a3, b4. }
9. Bd2 { Finishing the development. } 9... Bd6
{ Our bishop wasn't doing much on b4 anymore.   One might argue it'd be better for Black to finish their development with  9...Nbd7  . This would be a mistake, however, because we need to keep the option of developing the knight to c6 in case White goes for  10.Ne5  c5  11.f4  .  On c6, the knight puts pressure on d4. }
10. Rc1 { 11. Nb5 is the threat now, so we should cover the b5-square. } 10...
a6 11. Ne5 c5
{ When one player starts an attack on one of the flanks, the opponent should be ready to meet it with a punch in the center @@StartBracket@@if the kings castled to the same side@@EndBracket@@. }
12. f4 Nc6
{ You see why it was important not to hurry with the development of this knight? What would it be doing on d7 now? The answer is nothing. On c6, however, it attacks the pawn on d4 and there are no good ways for White to protect it:   13.Ne2  closes the path for White's queen @@StartBracket@@it wants to go to f3 and then to h3@@EndBracket@@, and it also loses control over e4, allowing Black to go for an immediate  13...Ne4  . }
13. Ng4 { White wants to meet  13...cxd4  with  14.Nxf6  and  15. Nxd5. } 13...
Be7
{ We've protected the d5-pawn and, at the same time, White has to do something about the hanging d4-pawn. There can be no talk of an attack on Black's king. }
