[Black "5.Bg5 h6 6.Bxf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops any e4-ideas White might have. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. Bg5
{ A rare case when White's dark-squared bishop does not develop to b2. The downside of this move is that Black hasn't castled yet, so ideas with h6, g5 and Ne4 are possible. }
5... h6
{ It's always useful to ask this bishop a question: Do you want to take on f6 or not? }
6. Bxf6
{ White claims that getting the desired e4-move on the board is worth trading the bishop. }
6... Qxf6 7. e4 Bb7
{ Targeting e4.  8.e5  is premature because of  8...Qf4  @@StartBracket@@the downside of not having the dark-squared bishop anymore@@EndBracket@@, with the imminent threat of Bxf3. }
8. Bd3 Bxc3+ { We're now ready to spoil White's pawn structure! } 9. bxc3 d6
{ Creating a flexible pawn structure for ourselves and keeping the c5- and e5-options both on the table. }
10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2
{ White is preparing e5. Although, even if we allow it to happen, it will be difficult to create any threats to our king without a dark-squared bishop. }
11... Nc6
{ Developing the last piece and stopping e5. At the same time, we prepare to fix White's pawn structure by playing e5 ourselves. Later, we should attack White's doubled c-pawns. The easiest way to do that is by playing Na5 and Ba6. }
