[Black "5.Bg5 h6 6.Bh4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here: 4. Bd2  (the mainline)  , 4. Nbd2 and 4. Nc3, which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops any e4-ideas White might have. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. Bg5
{ A rare case when White's dark-squared bishop does not develop to b2. The downside of this move is that Black hasn't castled yet, so ideas with h6, g5 and Ne4 are possible. }
5... h6
{ It's always useful to ask this bishop a question: Do you want to take on f6 or not? }
6. Bh4 { The most natural move. } 6... Bb7 { Stopping e4 once again. } 7. Nd2
e5 { An interesting pawn sacrifice! } 8. dxe5 Bxc3
{ An important intermediate move, spoiling White's pawn structure. If  9.exf6  , Black has  9...Bxf6  . }
9. bxc3 g5 10. exf6
{ This gets White into trouble, as the doubled c-pawns are much weaker than Black's doubled h-pawns, mainly because of Black's light-squared 'monster' bishop on the long diagonal. Castling will be a serious issue for White, as the queenside is not an option due to the compromised pawn structure, while the kingside can prove to be risky due to the open g-file and the strong b7-bishop. }
10... gxh4 11. Nf3 Nc6
{ A very important move! Black needs to take the d4-square away from White's queen. For example  11...Qxf6  would be a big mistake, as after  12.Qd4  Black cannot avoid exchanging the queens, which will solve all of White's king safety issues.  After the text move, Black will continue with 12... Qxf6 and then castle long, with much better chances thanks to the open g-file, the strong bishop, White's king safety issues and doubled c-pawns. }
*

