{ Once again, we spoil White's pawn structure, but this time we also win a central pawn in the process!   If instead we play  8...g5  with the idea to take on  e4  with the bishop, our prospects are not so good after  9.Bg3  Bxe4  10.h4  Rg8  11.hxg5  hxg5  12.Be5  followed by  12...--  13.Rh6  . If @@StartFEN@@rn2k2r/p1ppqp2/1p2pn1p/6p1/1bPPb2P/2N3B1/PP1N1PP1/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...g4  , White has  11.h5  with Bh4-ideas. }
9. bxc3 g5 10. Bg3 { Only move. } 10... Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Bxc7 d6
{ White is now forced to move their bishop for the 5th @@StartBracket@@!!!@@EndBracket@@ time, trading it for the knight on b8 which hasn't even moved once! Black will be better thanks to their better pawn structure @@StartBracket@@two pawn islands vs White's three pawn islands@@EndBracket@@. The king will be safe on the kingside. It's a bit open due to our pawn on g5, but there's no need to worry about it, as there are not enough pieces left for White to create an attack. Our plan will involve attacking White's doubled c-pawns, especially now that the c-file is open for our rooks. }
