[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. The Nimzo line 4. Nc3"]
[Black "5.Bg5 h6 6.Bh4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops any e4-ideas White might have. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. Bg5
{ A rare case when White's dark-squared bishop does not develop to b2. The downside of this move is that Black hasn't castled yet, so ideas with h6, g5 and Ne4 are possible. }
5... h6
{ It's always useful to ask this bishop a question: Do you want to take on f6 or not? }
6. Bh4 { The most natural move. } 6... Bb7 { Stopping e4 once again. } 7. e3
{ The most popular continuation in this position. However, I find it easier to play the resulting positions with Black. Let's check them out! }
7... g5 8. Bg3 { Only move. } 8... Ne4
{ The best square for our knight. Nxc3 is the threat now. } 9. Nd2
{ An interesting pawn sacrifice. It's dangerous to accept it, as after  9...Nxc3  10.bxc3  Bxc3  11.Rc1  , Black will be much behind in development. They might also get in trouble due to the weakened pawn structure on the kingside. }
9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 Nxg3
{ Without the dark-squared bishop, it will be difficult for White to exploit our weaknesses on the kingside. }
11. hxg3 d6 { Planning to finish the development and castle long, as usual. }
12. Rh2
{ White defends the g2-pawn so that the bishop can be released from its protection. }
12... Nd7 13. Be2 { White aims for a bishop trade. } 13... Qe7
{ But we'll just meet it with a long castle. } 14. Bf3 O-O-O
{ We'll slowly improve the position with f5 and a5, and try to target White's doubled pawns. In case White keeps their king in the center, we can even consider a breakthrough there. }
