1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3
{ White transposes to a Nimzo with 4. Nf3. Compared to the Nbd2-lines, White's knight is better-placed here, but it allows us to spoil White's pawn structure after Bxc3, bxc3. However, we must first make sure to develop in a way that stops any e4-ideas White might have. }
4... b6
{ The best way to fight against the e4-idea is to develop the bishop to b7. White has a wide choice here.   The most popular moves are  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  . }
5. Bg5
{ A rare case when White's dark-squared bishop does not develop to b2. The downside of this move is that Black hasn't castled yet, so ideas with h6, g5 and Ne4 are possible. }
5... h6
{ It's always useful to ask this bishop a question: Do you want to take on f6 or not? }
6. Bh4 { The most natural move. } 6... Bb7 { Stopping e4 once again. } 7. e3
{ The most popular continuation in this position. However, I find it easier to play the resulting positions with Black. Let's check them out! }
7... g5 8. Bg3 { Only move. } 8... Ne4
{ The best square for our knight. Nxc3 is the threat now. } 9. Qc2 Bxc3+ 10.
bxc3 { Making sure to compromise White's pawn structure. } 10... d6
{ Covering e5. } 11. Bd3 Nxg3
{ We can try to make use of the fact that White's bishop is no longer guarding the g2-pawn. }
12. fxg3
