12... g4
{ Forcing White's knight to the bad h4-square, as the g2-pawn would be lost otherwise. }
13. Nh4 Qg5
{ Attacking the pawn on e3, while also preparing to develop the knight to d7 and then castle long. }
14. O-O
{ An interesting pawn sacrifice. It's too dangerous for Black to accept it, as the king is still in the center. Opening the e-file would only make it more vulnerable. }
14... Nd7 { We just continue our development. } 15. Rf4
{ Protecting e3 and planning to double on the f-file. } 15... O-O-O 16. Qe2
{ Protecting the e3-pawn, thus threatening to take on f7 and g4. } 16... f5
{ Protecting both pawns with one move and creating a nice pawn chain! White should try to undermine it in order to create counterplay, otherwise the knight on h4 will be stuck there forever. }
17. e4 { Attacking the f5-pawn and trying to break Black's pawn chain. } 17...
Nf6
{ A strategical pawn sacrifice meant to avoid exchanging the bishops, as Black's bishop on b7 is currently a better piece than White's on d3. White has to do something about the e4-pawn, or else we'll just capture it with the knight. }
18. exf5 e5
{ Taking advantage of the fact that White's bishop on d3 is a tactical weakness!  19.dxe5  would be met by  19...dxe5  and the e5-pawn is untouchable, as the Bishop on d3 would remain unprotected. }
19. Rf2 Rhe8 { X-raying White's queen. } 20. Qc2 Qe3
{ Creating an unpleasant pin, while also attacking the d4-pawn. Even though White's knight can now jump to g6, there are no real prospects for it there, as it still has no routes to aim for. Because of White's doubled g-pawns, we don't even feel like we're a pawn down! Black has huge compensation for it: better pieces, a better pawn structure and a potential passer on the e-file. }
