d5
{ The e6-pawn, the base of Black's pawn chain, is our most vulnerable pawn, considering that its 'friend' is already on d6 and, as such, not able to support it. White tries to exploit it. }
17... exd5 18. cxd5
{ 18.Rxf5  would run into  18...Qg7  , attacking the pawn on c3, so White wouldn't have time to comfortably take back on d5.   18.Bxf5  would instead be met with  18...h5  , protecting g4 and with a likely transposition to the text move  18. cxd5. }
18... Bxd5 19. Bxf5 h5
{ Black's position is preferable. We have a healthy pawn structure and a clear plan: bring the knight to c5 @@StartBracket@@only possible after moving the king to b7 to get rid of the pin@@EndBracket@@ and then attack White's weaknesses on e3 and c3. The only worry might be the king's safety, but we must remember that, even if White wins the a7-pawn @@StartBracket@@e.g. by taking it with the queen@@EndBracket@@, the a8-square is covered by the bishop, so there's no mate threat at all.   For example:  20.Qa6+  Kb8  21.Ra4  Qxe3+  22.Kh1  Qxc3  23.Qxa7  Kc8  and Black's king is safe, while Black also has an extra pawn. I believe the strategical advantages in Black's position @@StartBracket@@the healthy pawn structure and the better-placed minor pieces@@EndBracket@@ should ultimately prove to be more important than the dynamics White is counting on. }
