[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Bogo-Indian 4.Nbd2 b6 5.g3 "]
[Black "7.a3 Bxd2+"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2
{ A move preferred by many strong GMs: Carlsen, Kramnik, Ding Liren, Giri... White wants to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board, trying to win the bishop pair after an eventual a3-Bxd2. Then it will be much easier for White to start their play on the queenside, as the dark-squared bishop supports the pawn expansion much better than a knight.   At the same time, White wants to achieve that without allowing Black to double the c-pawns, like in the lines with  4.Nc3  . }
4... b6 5. g3 { By choosing this move order, White transposes to the Catalan. }
5... Bb7
{ This is the preferred move nowadays. If instead  5...Ba6  White loses a tempo to defend the c4-pawn but after  6.Qc2  Black still has to go back with  6...Bb7  so as not to get in trouble on the long diagonal. Since the white queen wanted to leave the d1-square anyway, Black would lose some time here. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. a3 Bxd2+
{ Both taking on d2 and retreating to e7 are possible, as White cannot follow up with e4. I like 7... Bxd2 more, as it feels like Black has very easy and clear play here. The other option is examined as an alternative. }
8. Qxd2 Be4
{ This move not only stops e4 for good but it also doesn't allow any ideas with d5. Furthermore, after exd5 and Nh4, the bishop on e4 exploits the pin on the long diagonal. }
9. O-O d5
{ 10.cxd5  would be met by 10 ...  Qxd5  with fantastic control over the long diagonal.  11... Rd8 and  12... c5 or 12 ... Nc6 will follow, building up the pressure on the d4-pawn. }
10. Qc3
{ If  10.b3  then Black can continue with  10...dxc4  11.bxc4  and  11...Nbd7  , followed by  12.--  c5  after almost any of White's moves. Black is aiming to get a pawn structure with a7-b6 against White's a3-c4 on the queenside, where the c4-pawn will become a weakness. }
10... Nbd7
{ The development is completed! Imagine Black's bishop on b7 rather than on e4. This would be a 'normal' Catalan position where White is better due to the bishop pair. They could play Bf4, Rd1, Ne5... However, the bishop on e4 is a big improvement for Black. We don't have to worry about pins on the long diagonal after moves like Ne5. White will also never be able to make e4 happen, which would allow them to open up the position for their bishop pair. }
11. cxd5
{ With our bishop on e4, we almost never take back on d5 with the pawn. If possible, we take with the queen, otherwise, the knight is fine as well. The plan is to prepare c5 so that the pawn on c7 won't become a target at some point. }
11... Nxd5 12. Qc4
{ Once again, we see what a beast our bishop is! White's queen has to go to an awkward position rather than the preferable c2. }
12... Qb8
{ A typical move in Queen's Indian structures. It goes especially well with Be4, as the queen plans to go to b7, leading to a nice x-ray on the long light diagonal. We'll then follow up with Rfd8, Rac8 and c5. }
*

