[White "2. Bogo-Indian 4.Nbd2 b6 5.g3 "]
[Black "5.g3 Bb7 6.Bg2 O-O 7.a3 Be7 8.Qc2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2
{ A move preferred by many strong GMs: Carlsen, Kramnik, Ding Liren, Giri... White wants to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board, trying to win the bishop pair after an eventual a3-Bxd2. Then it will be much easier for White to start their play on the queenside, as the dark-squared bishop supports the pawn expansion much better than a knight.   At the same time, White wants to achieve that without allowing Black to double the c-pawns, like in the lines with  4.Nc3  . }
4... b6 5. g3 { By choosing this move order, White transposes to the Catalan. }
5... Bb7
{ This is the preferred move nowadays. If instead  5...Ba6  White loses a tempo to defend the c4-pawn but after  6.Qc2  Black still has to go back with  6...Bb7  so as not to get in trouble on the long diagonal. Since the white queen wanted to leave the d1-square anyway, Black would lose some time here. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. a3 Be7
{ White can either castle immediately  8.O-O  or first play  8.Qc2  to prepare e4. Our reaction is the same in both cases:  8... c5. }
8. Qc2 c5 { Attacking the center! The d4-pawn is hanging. } 9. e4
{ White tries to go for a hedgehog structure. However, it is not the best idea, as White's knight on d2 is misplaced. It would be much better on c3, from where it controls d5. }
9... cxd4 10. e5
{ Is a mistake here, as White will have problems with holding on to their e5-pawn. }
10... Ng4
{ Black takes advantage of the pin on the long light diagonal - the e5-pawn is hanging. }
11. Ng5
{ This is a tactical idea to be aware of @@StartBracket@@mate is being threatened on h7 and the b7-bishop is hanging@@EndBracket@@, though in this particular case it doesn't work. }
11... Bxg5 12. Bxb7 Nc6
{ We sacrifice the exchange, but we already have a pawn for it @@StartBracket@@d4@@EndBracket@@ and the e5-pawn is also weak, and so will be the complex of light squares around White's king after short castle. All these things grant Black more than enough compensation. }
13. Bxa8 Qxa8 { X-raying the rook on h1. } 14. O-O Bxd2
{ Now we win yet another pawn! } 15. Qxd2 Ncxe5
{ Threatening a nasty fork on f3 and attacking the c4-pawn. Black has a significant advantage! }
