[Black "8.O-O c5 9.b3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2
{ A move preferred by many strong GMs: Carlsen, Kramnik, Ding Liren, Giri... White wants to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board, trying to win the bishop pair after an eventual a3-Bxd2. Then it will be much easier for White to start their play on the queenside, as the dark-squared bishop supports the pawn expansion much better than a knight.   At the same time, White wants to achieve that without allowing Black to double the c-pawns, like in the lines with  4.Nc3  . }
4... b6 5. g3 { By choosing this move order, White transposes to the Catalan. }
5... Bb7
{ This is the preferred move nowadays. If instead  5...Ba6  White loses a tempo to defend the c4-pawn but after  6.Qc2  Black still has to go back with  6...Bb7  so as not to get in trouble on the long diagonal. Since the white queen wanted to leave the d1-square anyway, Black would lose some time here. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. a3 Be7
{ White can either castle immediately  8.O-O  or first play  8.Qc2  to prepare e4. Our reaction is the same in both cases:  8... c5. }
8. O-O c5
{ Attacking the center once again! It's important that Black doesn't hurry with playing d6 - this pawn might want to go to d5 in one move. White has a big choice now.   They can either try to go for a Benoni-like structure after  9.d5  or take  9.dxc5  trying to open up the dark long diagonal for their bishop @@StartBracket@@with the plan of playing b3 and Bb2@@EndBracket@@. Other possibilities are to consolidate the center with  9.e3  or to just ignore Black's last move and continue the development with  9.b3  . }
9. b3 { The most popular move. } 9... cxd4
{ We simplify the position. As we still have a little less space, the trades favor us. }
10. Bb2
{ White doesn't hurry to take the d4-pawn back, thus keeping their options open. They can now capture on d4 with both of their minor pieces. }
10... Qc7 { We are defending our tactical weakness: the b7-bishop. } 11. Bxd4
{ White tries to avoid exchanging the minor pieces. } 11... d6
{ Once again, we clear the d7-square for our b8-knight. } 12. Rc1 Nbd7 13. Re1
{ White wants to play 14. e4. } 13... Ne4
{ Black doesn't allow it! At the same time, as mentioned before, piece exchanges are favorable for us and White doesn't have a good way to avoid them: Nxd2 will follow, and then we can start preparing d5 with Rac8, Rfd8, Qb8, Qa8. }
