8... Nbd7
{ Le Quang Liem's favorite choice. I really like his approach to this line! }
9. Bb2 Ne4
{ Black wants to seal the center with f5 and then prepare some play on the kingside. }
10. Rc1 f5 11. a3
{ Realizing that Black is going to play on the kingside, White tries to organize their counterplay on the queenside. }
11... Be7 12. Ne1
{ White can also try to bring their knight to d3, get rid of our active knight on e4 with f3, and then prepare e4. }
12... a5 { Not allowing b4 anymore. } 13. Nd3 Re8
{ A solid waiting move. Black figured out that f3 isn't working out for White just yet and tempts them to go for it. }
14. f3 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 c5
{ White has weakened their dark squares and closed up their light bishop. Also, there is no knight on f3 any longer to support White's center, so why not attack the center? Black may then continue with Rc8 and Bf6 to prepare various simplifications in the center. }
