8. cxd5 exd5
{ This pawn structure is common in many openings. Ideally, Black shouldn't allow White Ne5 by playing Re8 and Bd6. It's very important for Black not to hurry with the development of the b8-knight. If White plays Ne5 and f4 with the idea to start an attack on the kingside, we should be able to answer with c5 followed by Nc6, putting pressure on d4. Of course, this type of attack works better for White when their bishop is not fianchettoed but stays on the b1-h7 diagonal, but we have to be aware of such possibilities. }
9. Ne5 Re8 10. f4 { White is not ready for such an expansion. } 10... c5
{ Do you know the saying that 'if one attacks on a flank, you should answer with an attack in the center?' Well, that's exactly the case here! }
11. a3 Bxd2
{ White is forced to take back with the queen, as otherwise, the pawn on d4 is falling. }
12. Qxd2 Nc6
{ Black successfully finished the development, while White is far from doing so, with the bishop still on c1 and the rook on a1, which won't enter the game any time soon. At the same time, White has to solve the issue of the hanging d4-pawn.   If  13.e3  we can play  13...Na5  @@StartBracket@@threatening a fork on b3@@EndBracket@@ and all of White's light squares are crying. Ne4 will eventually follow and then f6, getting rid of the only good piece White has - the knight on e5. }
