1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2
{ A move preferred by many strong GMs: Carlsen, Kramnik, Ding Liren, Giri... White wants to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board, trying to win the bishop pair after an eventual a3-Bxd2. Then it will be much easier for White to start their play on the queenside, as the dark-squared bishop supports the pawn expansion much better than a knight.   At the same time, White wants to achieve that without allowing Black to double the c-pawns, like in the lines with  4.Nc3  . }
4... b6 5. g3 { By choosing this move order, White transposes to the Catalan. }
5... Bb7
{ This is the preferred move nowadays. If instead  5...Ba6  White loses a tempo to defend the c4-pawn but after  6.Qc2  Black still has to go back with  6...Bb7  so as not to get in trouble on the long diagonal. Since the white queen wanted to leave the d1-square anyway, Black would lose some time here. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O d5
{ The transposition to the Catalan is complete! We couldn't avoid it, as White would eventually threaten to play e4 and we can't allow them to get so much space in the center. In this tabia, White has many options, but it seems we're doing fine in every line. What better proof can there be than the World Champion himself - Magnus Carlsen - going for this position repeatedly with Black? }
8. cxd5 exd5
{ This pawn structure is common in many openings. Ideally, Black shouldn't allow White Ne5 by playing Re8 and Bd6. It's very important for Black not to hurry with the development of the b8-knight. If White plays Ne5 and f4 with the idea to start an attack on the kingside, we should be able to answer with c5 followed by Nc6, putting pressure on d4. Of course, this type of attack works better for White when their bishop is not fianchettoed but stays on the b1-h7 diagonal, but we have to be aware of such possibilities. }
9. Ne5 Re8 10. Ndf3
{ White gives up the attacking ideas with f4 and tries to consolidate in the center. They finish the development and hope to put some pressure on our c7-pawn with Bf4, Qc2, Rac1, forcing it to move to c6, which would close up the b7-bishop and loosen our control of the e4-square. }
10... Ne4 { Preparing to disrupt White's perfect harmony in the center. } 11.
Bf4 f6
{ A great move which assures we'll never have to worry about the e5-square again! }
12. Nd3 Bf8
{ We avoid exchanging the bishops  (by moving the bishop to d6)  because White's d3-knight @@StartBracket@@which is limited at the moment@@EndBracket@@ would get a very nice square on f4. White's other minor pieces would also get more room for maneuvering, so we want to avoid that.   Black shouldn't be worried about the c7-pawn being weak, as it can easily be defended by either Na6 or c6. Instead, retreating the bishop to e7 would spoil the harmony of Black's pieces by obstructing the control over the e-file and getting in the way of the queen's potential rerouting to f7. }
13. Rc1 { White still hopes we'll play c6. } 13... Na6
{ It is important that we develop our knight to a6 rather than the usual d7. Our king is slightly weakened by f6, and after Qb3, Nd2, f3 we might face some problems with holding our ground in the center. That's why the knight should have the option of going to c7, from where it will both hold d5 and threaten Ne6, forcing White to give up some of their nice squares @@StartBracket@@the f4-bishop is ideally placed there@@EndBracket@@. }
