[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2
{ A move preferred by many strong GMs: Carlsen, Kramnik, Ding Liren, Giri... White wants to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board, trying to win the bishop pair after an eventual a3-Bxd2. Then it will be much easier for White to start their play on the queenside, as the dark-squared bishop supports the pawn expansion much better than a knight.   At the same time, White wants to achieve that without allowing Black to double the c-pawns, like in the lines with  4.Nc3  . }
4... b6 5. g3 { By choosing this move order, White transposes to the Catalan. }
5... Bb7
{ This is the preferred move nowadays. If instead  5...Ba6  White loses a tempo to defend the c4-pawn but after  6.Qc2  Black still has to go back with  6...Bb7  so as not to get in trouble on the long diagonal. Since the white queen wanted to leave the d1-square anyway, Black would lose some time here. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O d5
{ The transposition to the Catalan is complete! We couldn't avoid it, as White would eventually threaten to play e4 and we can't allow them to get so much space in the center. In this tabia, White has many options, but it seems we're doing fine in every line. What better proof can there be than the World Champion himself - Magnus Carlsen - going for this position repeatedly with Black? }
8. Ne5 { The mainline, trying to exploit the pin on the long diagonal. } 8...
a5
{ An important prophylactic move that stops b4. Now after  9.a3  , we can just retreat with  9...Be7  and White cannot follow up with b4. }
9. Qc2
{ Preparing to open up the position with e4 but, once again, this move has some downsides, too: our rook will come very smoothly to c8 sooner rather than later, and the d4-pawn is left without any support.   If  9.Nb1  with the idea of going a3 and Nc3, Black should continue the development by playing  9...Nbd7  . After  10.a3  , we can retreat with  10...Bd6  , challenging the e5-knight. If then  11.Bf4  @@StartBracket@@protecting the e5-knight@@EndBracket@@, Black can continue with  11...Qc8  , protecting the bishop on b7 and preparing to take on c4. Then we'll exchange the light-squared bishop and prepare c5. If White tries to avoid this by playing  12.cxd5  , we'll take with a minor piece, e.g.  12...Bxd5  to make sure the b7-bishop doesn't remain passive and closed due to the pawn on d5. }
9... c5 { Trying to undermine White's center! } 10. a3
{ Not a dangerous move. } 10... Bxd2 11. Qxd2
{ The only good way to recapture, as the d4-pawn was hanging. } 11... Qc7
{ Protecting the bishop and planning to take on c4, with further simplifications to follow and an equal position. }
