1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. e3
{ A quiet setup. White wants to finish the development on the kingside, then fianchetto the bishop to b2 and prepare e4. }
5... Bb7 6. Be2
{ A modest move. We get an improved version of the mainline, as the bishop on e2 no longer supports e4. }
6... O-O 7. O-O d5
{ One must remember to always fight for the control in the center. Given that c5 is out of the question for now, as our bishop would feel trapped on b4, this is the only way to go! }
8. a3 Be7 9. b4
{ It's important to remember that whenever White is ready to play c5, we must be able to do so ourselves. }
9... c5 10. bxc5 bxc5
{ There is nothing to worry about here, as both sides are at the same stage of their development. }
11. Rb1 Qc8
{ Thee queen is better placed on c8 than on c7, as it does a much better job at supporting the move Ba6 from here. }
12. Qb3 { White tries to put some pressure on the open b-file. } 12... Ba6
{ A nice square for our bishop, getting White's bishop into an unpleasant pin. }
13. Bb2 Nbd7
{ With a balanced, almost symmetrical position. We plan on playing Rb8, after which we might consider simplifications in the center. }
