[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. e3
{ A quiet setup. White wants to finish the development on the kingside, then fianchetto the bishop to b2 and prepare e4. }
5... Bb7 6. Bd3
{ The optimal placement for the bishop, as it supports the e4-plan. } 6... O-O
7. O-O
{ If  7.a3  then  7...Bxd2  8.Qxd2  d5  and we reach almost the same position as in the line with 4.Nbd2 b6 5.a3 The only difference is that White's bishop is on d3 rather than on e2, but Black's approach should be the same. }
7... d5 { Once again, fighting for the center and preventing e4. } 8. a3 Be7
{ We retreat to e7 rather than d6 because if White plays b4, we don't want the c5-threat to come with a tempo. }
9. b3 { White chooses the standard plan with the fianchetto of their bishop. }
9... Nbd7 10. Bb2 c5
{ Now that our bishop is safe on e7, we increase the pressure in the center. }
11. Qe2 { Preparing e4. } 11... a5
{ An interesting move! One idea is to compromise White's c4-pawn by playing a4. Another idea is to prevent b4 so that, after an eventual capture on c5, we can take back with a piece. As White's knight is on d2 rather than c3, the weakness of the b5-square is not critical.   12.Rfd1  can already be met by  12...a4  . }
12. dxc5 Nxc5 { Now our knight is on a very nice square! } 13. Bc2 Rc8
{ Eyeing the c2-bishop. } 14. Rfd1 { White is x-raying our queen as well. }
14... dxc4 15. Nxc4 Bd5
{ A nice move, enabled by our good control over the e4-square! White can't make use of the pin on the d-file for now and later they won't be able to either, as we'll play 16... Qc7 with a balanced position. Black will try to create some play on the c-file, targeting the unstable knight on c4 and White's potential weakness on b3. }
