[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Bogo-Indian 4.Nbd2 b6 5.a3"]
[Black "6.Bxd2 Bb7 7.e3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2
{ A move preferred by many strong GMs: Carlsen, Kramnik, Ding Liren, Giri... White wants to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board, trying to win the bishop pair after an eventual a3-Bxd2. Then it will be much easier for White to start their play on the queenside, as the dark-squared bishop supports the pawn expansion much better than a knight. }
4... b6 { First step: finishing the development! } 5. a3
{ White wants us to decide as soon as possible what we're doing about our bishop on b4. There's no other choice than taking on d2 because e4 would follow otherwise. For example  5...Be7  6.e4  . }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2
{ If White captures with the bishop, we go for the plan with d6 and e5. We have enough time for that. }
6... Bb7 7. e3
{ This setup allows our b7-bishop to be 'the master of the long diagonal'. This means we can go for our d6/e5-plan without any worries. }
7... d6 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. O-O
{ If  9.Qc2  , not allowing us to play Ne4 anymore, then  9...c5!  followed by  10.--  Rc8  , x-raying White's queen and preparing to castle. Then we play d5, either immediately or after taking on d4. }
9... O-O 10. b4 { White stays true to their queenside expansion. } 10... e5
{ So we also stay true to our d6/e5-idea, which we might follow up with an attack on the kingside thanks to our super strong b7-bishop! }
11. Bc2 Qe7
{ An important thing to keep in mind is that before attacking on any of the flanks, we must stabilize the center. We can achieve that by playing e4 followed by d5. The bishop on b7 will either go to f5 via c8 or to a6. }
*

