[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Bogo-Indian 4.Nbd2 b6 5.a3"]
[Black "6.Bxd2 Bb7 7.g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2
{ A move preferred by many strong GMs: Carlsen, Kramnik, Ding Liren, Giri... White wants to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board, trying to win the bishop pair after an eventual a3-Bxd2. Then it will be much easier for White to start their play on the queenside, as the dark-squared bishop supports the pawn expansion much better than a knight. }
4... b6 { First step: finishing the development! } 5. a3
{ White wants us to decide as soon as possible what we're doing about our bishop on b4. There's no other choice than taking on d2 because e4 would follow otherwise. For example  5...Be7  6.e4  . }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2
{ If White captures with the bishop, we go for the plan with d6 and e5. We have enough time for that. }
6... Bb7 7. g3
{ White doesn't give up the control of the long diagonal so easily. } 7... O-O
8. Bg2 d6
{ Preparing to finish our development with Nbd7, after which we can choose either e5 or c5. }
9. O-O Nbd7 10. b4
{ As said before, White's play is on the queenside, as they have more space there. White will try to prepare c5. }
10... Qe7 11. Qb3
{ Connecting the rooks and x-raying the b7-bishop. Both are useful when preparing c5. }
11... Be4
{ A very important move! Black gets rid of the potential tactical weakness on b7 without giving up control over the light-squared diagonal. On the other hand, the e5-plan won't work that well anymore, as there would no longer be the threat of following up with e4. We have to come up with a different plan! }
12. Rfd1 a5
{ We want to open up the a-file by taking on b4. The plan then is to play b5! It'd be great for us if White placed all of their queenside pawns on dark squares, as that would make their dark-squared bishop less dangerous. At the same time, the light squares @@StartBracket@@d5, c4, e4@@EndBracket@@ will be weakened after we play b5, and we'll have extra squares to maneuver our pieces around @@StartBracket@@Bd5, Ne4, Nb6@@EndBracket@@. Taking on b5 wins a pawn, of course, but we will be able to recapture it at some point after Rb8 and Qd7. }
13. Bc3 { White chooses not to touch their queenside pawn structure. } 13...
axb4 14. axb4 b5
{ A typical move meant to weaken White's light squares. The price we pay for it is not high - White's extra pawn will be doubled, thus vulnerable. }
15. cxb5 Nb6
{ Now all the light squares are ours! We can later get our pawn back with Qd7-Qxb5. }
