[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Bogo-Indian 4.Nbd2 b6 5.a3"]
[Black "6.Bxd2 Bb7 7.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2
{ A move preferred by many strong GMs: Carlsen, Kramnik, Ding Liren, Giri... White wants to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board, trying to win the bishop pair after an eventual a3-Bxd2. Then it will be much easier for White to start their play on the queenside, as the dark-squared bishop supports the pawn expansion much better than a knight. }
4... b6 { First step: finishing the development! } 5. a3
{ White wants us to decide as soon as possible what we're doing about our bishop on b4. There's no other choice than taking on d2 because e4 would follow otherwise. For example  5...Be7  6.e4  . }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2
{ If White captures with the bishop, we go for the plan with d6 and e5. We have enough time for that. }
6... Bb7 7. Bg5
{ This move can't be good. We know that we must develop in the opening phase, rather than move the same piece several times. Surprisingly, this move has been played quite a few times - it's actually the most popular one! }
7... d6 { Our all-time favorite move in our Bogo approach! } 8. e3 h6
{ It's useful to ask the g5-bishop an existential question: Why are you going to h4? Or do you want to trade on f6? }
9. Bxf6 Qxf6 { White has given up their bishop pair, and for what? } 10. Be2
Nd7 { Just continuing our development. } 11. O-O O-O
{ We have a nice position! Our bishop is obviously better than White's. We plan on attacking the center with c5. Note that we don't go for the e5-plan here, as after d5 our bishop on b7 will become a bad piece. If White tries to do the same after c5, we just take on d5 and switch to a Benoni-like structure, where the d5-pawn becomes a target. }
