[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Bogo-Indian 4.Nbd2 b6 5.a3"]
[Black "6.Qxd2 Bb7 7.b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2
{ A move preferred by many strong GMs: Carlsen, Kramnik, Ding Liren, Giri... White wants to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board, trying to win the bishop pair after an eventual a3-Bxd2. Then it will be much easier for White to start their play on the queenside, as the dark-squared bishop supports the pawn expansion much better than a knight. }
4... b6 { First step: finishing the development! } 5. a3
{ White wants us to decide as soon as possible what we're doing about our bishop on b4. There's no other choice than taking on d2 because e4 would follow otherwise. For example  5...Be7  6.e4  . }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7
{ As is usual in this structure, White has to decide where to develop their light-squared bishop: to g2, or to e2/d3. An extra option here is to immediately start with the pawn expansion on the queenside. }
7. b4
{ Usually, it is premature to start the pawn expansion on the queenside before castling. }
7... O-O 8. Bb2 a5
{ A typical move, trying to get White to determine the pawn structure on the queenside. }
9. e3 { A logical way to continue the development. } 9... Ne4
{ Black is trying to put some pressure on the b4-pawn, as White still needs some more moves to finish their development and get a comfortable advantage. }
10. Qc2 axb4
{ A few trades are convenient for us, as we have a bit less space. At the same time, the b4-pawn will now become vulnerable. }
11. axb4 Rxa1+ 12. Bxa1 Qe7
{ Now defending the pawn with  13.Qb3  doesn't work well in light of  13...Na6  with a further attack on b4, and White will have to make a pawn move anyway. So why help us with our development? }
13. c5 f5
{ A useful move that petrifies our knight on e4. It also highlights that our play should be on the light squares @@StartBracket@@d5 and c6@@EndBracket@@, keeping the position's character closed. White has the bishop pair and freeing them is not an option for us! }
14. Be2
{ GM Naiditsch went wrong here by playing  14...Nc6  against the World Champion Carlsen in 2015 @@StartBracket@@Grenke@@EndBracket@@ and leaving his bishop out of play. As a result, he struggled the whole game and eventually lost. }
14... Bd5
{ The bishop should go ahead and then the knight will come to c6 too. } 15. O-O
Nc6
{ Not only is the pawn on b4 hanging now but also Ra8-Ra2 is coming, with very unpleasant threats on the queenside. }
16. b5 Nb4 17. Qb2
{ It might look like our knight is trapped: we can't play  17...bxc5  because of  18.dxc5  and now  18...Qxc5  doesn't work due to the mate on g7, while taking  18...Nxc5  would lose the knight on b4. }
17... Na2
{ The final touch! Now our knight will always be able to escape via c3. At the same time, White has to solve serious problems with their compromised pawn structure: the c5-pawn is hanging! }
*

