4... b6 { First step: finishing the development! } 5. a3
{ White wants us to decide as soon as possible what we're doing about our bishop on b4. There's no other choice than taking on d2 because e4 would follow otherwise. For example  5...Be7  6.e4  . }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7
{ As is usual in this structure, White has to decide where to develop their light-squared bishop: to g2, or to e2/d3. An extra option here is to immediately start with the pawn expansion on the queenside. }
7. b4
{ Usually, it is premature to start the pawn expansion on the queenside before castling. }
7... O-O 8. Bb2 a5
{ A typical move, trying to get White to determine the pawn structure on the queenside. }
9. b5 d6 10. e3 c5
{ An interesting move. We want to open up the c-file so that the c4-pawn becomes a possible target. }
11. bxc6 Nxc6
{ Black has given up the control in the center, but we plan on attacking c4. White has no other choice than allow us to play a4 and free the nice a5-square for our knight, as 12. a4 would weaken b4 too much. }
12. Bd3 a4 13. O-O
{ White finally finished their development and is now ready to start something in the center with e4, trying to open up the position for their bishop pair. }
13... Na5 { A nasty fork is coming! } 14. Qe2 Nb3 15. Rad1 Be4
{ An important move, not allowing White to play e4 themselves, while also getting rid of White's bishop pair. The exchange of the light-squared bishops would be convenient for Black, as it makes the weakness of the b3-square even more noticeable. We might continue with Rc8 and d5. }
