Qxd5
{ And now we finally reveal our intention: recapturing on d5 with the queen rather than with the pawn! Now Black is the master of the light diagonal and we'll follow up with putting some extra pressure on the d4-pawn. }
9. Qg5
{ If White tries to trade queens, we just continue our development, claiming that the endgame would be convenient for us. }
9... O-O 10. Qxd5 Bxd5
{ Recapturing with a piece again! It would be strange to take with  10...exd5  and close the diagonal for our own bishop. }
11. Bg2 Nc6
{ An unorthodox move! It's usually better to avoid developing the knight in front of the pawn, especially when that line is open for our opponent, but here, with our bishop on d5, no one will be able to disturb our knight on c6. Meanwhile, we'll put some pressure on White's d4-pawn. }
12. O-O Rad8 { Now Bxf3 followed by Nxd4 is the threat! } 13. e3
{ White's dark-squared bishop is now stuck in a passive position, with no potential of getting active anytime soon. }
13... a5
{ Not allowing any counterplay with b4. If allowed, we'd love to follow up with a4, fixing White's pawns and underlining the light-square weaknesses in White's camp @@StartBracket@@b3, c4, e4@@EndBracket@@. We might then continue with Na5-Nb3, c5. }
