{ If White chooses to finish their development before starting the pawn expansion on the queenside, Black will have just enough time to organize something in the center. }
7... O-O 8. Be2 d5
{ If White castles now, we'll just take on c4 and claim to have a good position, as White moved their bishop twice @@StartBracket@@ Be2, Bxc4@@EndBracket@@. We should follow up by preparing c5. }
9. b3 { Getting ready to take on c4 with the pawn. } 9... Nbd7
{ Finishing the development and preparing c5. } 10. O-O c5 11. Bb2
{ White has also finished their development. The center is very tense and we have to carefully consider the outcome of every capture before making any moves. Coming to the conclusion that there are no serious threats, Anish Giri chose to bring one more piece closer to the center. }
11... Rc8 12. Rac1 Ne4
{ It makes sense to force White's queen onto an x-rayed file. } 13. Qc2
{ Here Anish Giri chose  13...dxc4  followed  14.bxc4  Nd6  in an online rapid game. It seems like this choice consolidates White's center. We will try a different approach, but with the same Nd6-idea. }
13... cxd4
{ Now our x-ray might become dangerous! At the same time, we want to keep the b2-bishop closed, as taking on d4 with a piece doesn't really work due to  14.Nxd4  14...dxc4  , after which White would have to weaken their pawn structure with  15.bxc4  , as  15.Bxc4  is too dangerous in light of the pin on the c-file. }
14. exd4 Nd6
{ We add some pressure on the c4-pawn and we'll continue in the same manner: Ba6, Qe7, or even Qf6, and double on the c-file. Black has a perfectly fine position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Bogo-Indian 4.Bd2 Qe7 5.Qc2 & 5.a3"]
[Black "5.Qc2 Bxd2+ 6.Nbxd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Qc2
{ This move works well with the e3/Bd3-plan, as e4 will no longer be a threat White has to worry about, but the price to pay is the suboptimal place on d2 for the b1-knight @@StartBracket@@it would prefer to be on c3@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2 d6
{ One of the reasons I like the Bogo-Indian: the plan is usually crystal-clear for Black. We go for d6 and e5 in most cases. }
7. e4
{ Doesn't work well combined with Qc2, which was designed for the e3-plan. }
7... e5 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O a5
{ We'll finish the development with Bg4 and Nc6 if White doesn't play d5. If they do, our knight on b8 will go to c5. That's the reason why we played a5 - to make sure a pawn on b4 won't stand in the way of our plans. }
*

