[White "5. Bogo-Indian 4.Bd2 Qe7 5.Qc2 & 5.a3"]
[Black "5.Qc2 Bxd2+ 6.Nbxd2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Qc2
{ This move works well with the e3/Bd3-plan, as e4 will no longer be a threat White has to worry about, but the price to pay is the suboptimal place on d2 for the b1-knight @@StartBracket@@it would prefer to be on c3@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2 d6
{ One of the reasons I like the Bogo-Indian: the plan is usually crystal-clear for Black. We go for d6 and e5 in most cases. }
7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 e5
{ You see, now White is prepared for e4 and we'll have to lose one more move @@StartBracket@@Re8@@EndBracket@@ to make e4 a real threat. }
9. O-O-O
{ An original line! White castles long, hoping to start an attack on our king. }
9... Nc6 10. a3 Bg4
{ Unfortunately for White, their center is not stable. We want to take on f3 and then either win the d4-pawn or play e4 with a fork. }
11. d5 Nb8
{ It might look like our knight is heading to the already known path of d7-c5. It's not the case here. We can instead try another idea with Rc8 followed by c6 in order to open the c-file. We know that in positions with castles on different sides, the player with a faster attack has better chances. }
12. h3 Bxf3 { Now  13.Nxf3  runs into a fork after  13...e4  . } 13. gxf3 Nbd7
{ Now the above-mentioned c6/Rc8-plan gives Black better chances! Our king is safer. We can stop White's attack with g6, Nh5 and f5 if we get too worried about it. }
*

