[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Qc2
{ This move works well with the e3/Bd3-plan, as e4 will no longer be a threat White has to worry about, but the price to pay is the suboptimal place on d2 for the b1-knight @@StartBracket@@it would prefer to be on c3@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2 d6
{ One of the reasons I like the Bogo-Indian: the plan is usually crystal-clear for Black. We go for d6 and e5 in most cases. }
7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 e5
{ You see, now White is prepared for e4 and we'll have to lose one more move @@StartBracket@@Re8@@EndBracket@@ to make e4 a real threat. }
9. O-O Re8
{ The small downside of this move is that the rook will no longer support f5 after the exchanges in the center. }
10. dxe5 dxe5 { Insisting on delivering the fork! } 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4
{ How nice it would be if our rook was still on f8, right? But one can't have it all sometimes so we'll have to prepare it first. }
12... g6 13. c5
{ White figured out that they can't stop us from playing f5, so they prepare for it instead! Now the bishop on d5 will always be able to retreat in case we disturb it with c6. That's why we don't hurry with it. }
13... a5
{ Not allowing a pawn expansion on the queenside, while also preparing a new route for our b8-knight. }
14. Rfd1 Na6 { The pawn on c5 would be a nice treat! } 15. Rac1 c6
{ The knight comes to c7, then we might consider f5, e4 and Be6. If White's rook tries to infiltrate on d6, we can make it move away with Nb5. }
