[White "5. Bogo-Indian 4.Bd2 Qe7 5.Qc2 & 5.a3"]
[Black "5.a3 Bxd2+ 6.Qxd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. a3
{ White tries to force the matters. a3 is a useful move, as it covers the b4-square @@StartBracket@@no more Qb4+ threats@@EndBracket@@ and prepares White's pawn expansion on the queenside @@StartBracket@@with b4@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bxd2+
{ Black's plan will be similar after all of the captures. After castling, we'll play d6, then e5, and, depending on what White will do about their pawn structure in the center, we'll choose our plan accordingly. }
6. Qxd2 O-O { First step: complete the development! } 7. Nc3 d6 8. e3
{ This is a way to ensure White will keep control over the d4-square, so it will not potentially become a weakness as in the variations with e4. }
8... e5
{ On the other hand, the downside of e3  (instead of e4)  is that we might play e4 ourselves! }
9. Qc2 Bg4
{ Threatening to take on d4, making use of the nice x-ray on the e-file! } 10.
Be2
{ White is now ready to meet  10...Bxf3  with  11.Bxf3  and Black won't have time to capture on d4 because the b7-pawn is hanging. }
10... Nbd7 { Just calmy finishing our development. } 11. O-O c6
{ Covering the d5-square. Black's plan will be to close the center with e4 and then try an attack on the kingside, perhaps with h5-h4-h3. }
