[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. a3
{ White tries to force the matters. a3 is a useful move, as it covers the b4-square @@StartBracket@@no more Qb4+ threats@@EndBracket@@ and prepares White's pawn expansion on the queenside @@StartBracket@@with b4@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bxd2+
{ Black's plan will be similar after all of the captures. After castling, we'll play d6, then e5, and, depending on what White will do about their pawn structure in the center, we'll choose our plan accordingly. }
6. Nbxd2
{ The mainline, though it looks to me that the knight is not as happy on d2 as it would be on c3, from where it would not only control e4 but also d5. }
6... d6
{ White has a few options here, though all of them will be met by the same reaction: short castle followed by e5. We already have a feel of this pawn structure and now we'll see the possible plans. }
7. e4 e5
{ Once again, White faces a choice on how to handle the pawn structure in the center. They can close it with d5, take on e5 or wait a bit by defending the e4-pawn. }
8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Bg4 { The best square to develop our bishop! } 10. Qc2 Nh5
{ The main advantage of having exchanged the dark-squared bishops is that we can now try to infiltrate by making use of the vulnerable dark squares. }
11. g3
{ A move White doesn't make out of a healthy position. Now all the light squares around White's king become weak and we might try an attack on the kingside! }
11... Nd7
{ Finishing our development and simultaneously we stop White from playing c5. }
12. Rfc1 c5
{ We seal the center. It's the first step one must take before starting something on one of the flanks - the center must be stable! }
13. d5 g6
{ As planned, an attack on the kingside will follow. We prepare f5 and try to either open the f-file for our rook or even play f4. The knight on h5 can go to g7 and then we'll have additional ideas with fxe4 followed by Nf5 and Nd4. White's counterplay on the queenside is too slow. Even if they play b4, they will still not threaten anything, as we're ready to capture on c5 with the knight. In any case, if we feel the pressure on c5 is becoming dangerous, we can always play b6. }
