[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Bogo-Indian 4.Bd2 Qe7 5.Nc3"]
[Black "5.Nc3 b6 6.e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Nc3
{ White's idea is to get a position with the bishop pair @@StartBracket@@Black will eventually have to take on c3@@EndBracket@@ and then open up the position for them. We can therefore deduce that Black should either try to keep the position closed, or eliminate one of White's bishops. This line reminds us a bit of the Nimzo. }
5... b6 6. e3
{ This is the most straightforward setup for White, where they calmly develop the kingside and then prepare e4. On the other hand, it allows the bishop on b7 to reign over the long diagonal. Our plan will keep this in mind. }
6... Bb7 7. Bd3 { The inferior  7.Be2  is shown inone of the model games. }
7... O-O 8. O-O d6
{ Black delays the capture on c3 so that White loses a tempo with a3 to force us to take the knight. At the same time, we continue our development with Nbd7. Then we can either play e5 @@StartBracket@@a solid plan@@EndBracket@@ or take on c3, followed by Ne4 and f5, starting a typical attack on the kingside @@StartBracket@@a more ambitious plan@@EndBracket@@. We should remember to keep control over the e4-square, not allowing White to play e4 themselves. When they are ready to do so, Black should be able to take on c3 and play Ne4. }
9. a3 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Ne4
{ This position perfectly illustrates the downside of White having developed the light-squared bishop to d3 rather than fianchettoing it. }
11. Be1 { White is not willing to part with their bishop pair so easily. }
11... Nd7 12. b4 f5
{ This position is full of play! White will try to organize something on the queenside. Black should keep an eye on it @@StartBracket@@maybe by playing c5 at some point to hinder White's pawn expansion@@EndBracket@@ and, at the same time, counterattack on the kingside. One idea is to bring the rook into the attack via f6 to either g6 or h6. }
