[Round "?"]
[White "7. Bogo-Indian 4.Bd2 Qe7 5.Nc3"]
[Black "6.g3  with 10.Be1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Nc3
{ White's idea is to get a position with the bishop pair @@StartBracket@@Black will eventually have to take on c3@@EndBracket@@ and then open up the position for them. We can therefore deduce that Black should either try to keep the position closed, or eliminate one of White's bishops. This line reminds us a bit of the Nimzo. }
5... b6 6. g3 { White doesn't want to concede the long diagonal. } 6... Bb7 7.
Bg2 O-O 8. O-O
{ As White's king is much more secure here than in the setup with e3, we choose a different plan, connected to d6-c5. Some of the resulting positions will remind us a bit of the Benoni structures. }
8... Bxc3
{ We don't wait for White to play a3 but proceed with our plan immediately, as there are no more useful waiting moves.   If Black plays  8...d6  @@StartBracket@@the most played move in the position, but already a mistake@@EndBracket@@, White has the option of playing  9.d5!  when after  9...e5  our bishop on b7 is 'dead' and we still have too many minor pieces on the board for the little space we have.   Instead, after  9...exd5  White has the strong  10.Nd4!  leading to a very dangerous initiative thanks to the bishop pair and the unpleasant pin on the long light diagonal. }
9. Bxc3 Ne4
{ We would love to ruin White's pawn structure and double the c-pawns if they allow us to do so. }
10. Be1
{ The only way to avoid exchanging the bishops and thus keep the bishop pair. The downside is that the rook on f1 will have a hard time getting into the game. }
10... c5 { Attacking the center immediately! } 11. d5
{ This would be a positional mistake, as, without the knight on c3, White has a hard time defending the pawn on d5 and controlling the center. }
11... exd5 12. cxd5 f5
{ Black will play d6, then Na6-Nc7, increasing the pressure on the d5-pawn. } *

