1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3
{ The main move. White has some other options as well. We examine them in the corresponding chapters. }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2
{ This is not where the knight wanted to end up - it would prefer to be on c3, from where it would not only support the e4-move but also control the d5-square! Now we can play the 'old' setup with d6 and e5. }
6... d6 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O e5 9. dxe5
{ Taking the pressure off in the center is not a good idea for White, as we'll be able to nicely develop our knight to c6 and then organize some play on the kingside after playing e4. If White instead plays e4, the d4-square will be weak, so we can occupy the d-file and place our knight on the d4-outpost. }
9... dxe5 10. Ng5 Nc6 11. Bxc6 bxc6
{ The light squares around White's king are now weakened! } 12. Qc2 h6 13. Nge4
Nh7 { A nice attack on the kingside is coming, with f5, e4, f4, Ng5. } *

