1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3
{ The main move. White has some other options as well. We examine them in the corresponding chapters. }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2
{ This is not where the knight wanted to end up - it would prefer to be on c3, from where it would not only support the e4-move but also control the d5-square! Now we can play the 'old' setup with d6 and e5. }
6... d6 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O e5 9. e4 a5
{ An important move that stops a possible pawn expansion on the queenside after White closes the center with d5. It also secures us a nice place for the b8-knight on c5, like in the best King's Indian tradition! }
10. d5 { White loses some tempi, as we can head on to c5 without losing time. }
10... Na6 11. Ne1 Nc5 12. Qe2 Bd7
{ The bishop is well-placed on d7, as it might support playing on the kingside with f5, as well as on the queenside with ideas like c6 and/or b5. }
13. Nd3 b6
{ 'Petrifying' our c5-knight. We are happy to open the b-file if White captures on c5. }
14. b3 h5
{ The favorite move of Alpha Zero! Now that White's knight is no longer on f3, we can play on the kingside. }
15. h3 h4 16. g4 Nh7
{ Now White's dark squares are weak and the bishop on g2 is not exactly a happy piece, considering that almost all of White's pawns are on light squares. We can choose between maneuvering our knight on the dark squares on the kingside or organizing an attack on the queenside with Rfb8 and b5. }
