13... e5
{ We tempt White to get the pawn back, but that would be a mistake, as after Bh3+ and O-O Black's development would be finished while White still struggles to find a secure place for their king. }
14. Kg2 { Protecting against Bh3+. } 14... exd4 15. exd4 O-O
{ White has compensation for the sacrificed pawn, but Black is also doing fine: We've solved our main issue - the passive bishop on c8 - and now it's on a very nice open diagonal! The position is balanced. Our play must involve attacking the isolated d4-pawn, but not before we finish our development  @@StartBracket@@with Be6 perhaps, then Rad8, Qb6 or Qd6@@EndBracket@@ }
