{ The difference to @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppppqppp/2n1pn2/8/2PP4/1P3NP1/P2QPP1P/RN2KB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...d5  , where White's pawn is on a2 rather than a3, is that the b3-c4 pawn chain is now vulnerable and Black will be able to attack it with a4. White won't be able to count on the a2-pawn to keep the pawn chain intact. }
9. Bg2 { 9.Nc3  would make no difference, as  9...a4  would follow anyway. }
9... a4 10. cxd5 Na5
{ A very important intermediate move which exploits the vulnerability of the b3-pawn. }
11. dxe6 Bxe6
{ Where White has no better option than to sacrifice an exchange for which they will have some compensation, but it won't be enough for more than a draw. }
