8. Nc3 a4 9. d5 { White wants to get as much space in the center as possible. }
9... Nb4 10. Rc1 { Going away from the the x-ray on the a-file. } 10... exd5
11. cxd5
{ Taking on d5 with a knight isn't a good option for White, because the side with less space is always happy to trade a few extra pieces for more space to manoeuver the the remaining ones around. }
11... axb3 12. axb3 O-O
{ Bringing the king to safety, then planning to solve the issue of the potential weakness on c7 by preparing c6, but not before playing d6 first to open up the bishop. }
13. Bg2 d6 14. O-O c6
{ While White was finishing off the development, we prepared c6 to solve the problem of the c7-pawn. The position is balanced. White has more space and better control of the center, but Black has control over the a-file and the very nice b4-square for the knight. The bishop will go to d7 @@StartBracket@@but not before we take on d5@@EndBracket@@, then the queen can be rerouted to b6, if White chooses to play  15.e4  .   If White instead plays  15.dxc6  , Black's bishop will have many good options to choose from after  15...bxc6  : a6, e6, d7. }
