8. Nc3 a4
{ An interesting pawn sacrifice! White has to choose between spoiling their pawn structure @@StartBracket@@if taking on a4 with the pawn@@EndBracket@@ and giving up the control over the e4- and b4-squares @@StartBracket@@if capturing with the knight@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Rb1 axb3 10. axb3 d5
{ Comparing this position to the one with 7... d5, we can see several improvements for Black: We have control of the a-file; we've also exchanged the pawns on this file, knowing that exchanges are convenient for the side with less space. There is one more hidden advantage, which we'll discover a bit later. }
11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O Rd8
{ X-raying the queen on d2 and threatening to take on c4 and then play e5. }
13. Qf4 Nh5
{ The queen on f4 is placed very nicely: it both defends the pawn on d4 and eyes our c7-pawn @@StartBracket@@threatening some Nb5@@EndBracket@@. We must force it into a worse position! }
14. Qe3 Nf6
{ Black would be happy with a repetition, as we are still a half step away from equalizing due to our unsolved bad bishop issue. }
15. Rfd1 Bd7
{ One more extra thing to count on in this position is the b4-square for out c6-knight. Imagine the a-pawns still on a2 and a7. White could always play a3 in this case and get our knight to move away, but now that's not possible! }
16. Rbc1 Nb4
{ Our knight is multifunctional on b4! It defends the d5-pawn and it also controls important squares in White's camp @@StartBracket@@d3, c2@@EndBracket@@, making it less comfortable for White to maneuver around. }
17. Ne5 Be8
{ Now the position is balanced. White has better control in the center, but we will have our counterplay on the a-file with Ra3, targeting the b3-pawn, followed by Rda8. }
