5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nc6
{ An interesting move which has become very fashionable lately. It feels a bit strange to develop the knight in front of the c7-pawn, but it has its purpose: to take the e5-square away from the knight on f3! We also threaten Ne4 followed by Qb4+, so White should do something about it. }
7. Nc3 d5
{ White has a few possibilities here:   8.cxd5  claiming that they have an advantage due to our strangely placed knight on c6 in a Carlsbad structure.   8.Ne5  , forcing Black to take with  8...dxc4  , then take on  9.Nxc6  , and continue by playing against our spoiled pawn structure.   Play  8.Bg2  to continue the development, allowing us to take on  8...dxc4  but gaining space in the center in return, and thus attempt to claim the advantage due to our difficulties in finishing our development on the queenside. }
