{ This structure reminds us somewhat of the Catalan... We need to be fast in trying to get rid of our tripled pawns on the queenside, but first, we should exchange the bishops if White allows us to do so. }
10. Bg2 O-O 11. Bxc6 Rb8
{ White got their pawn back, but now they don't have enough time to stop us from playing either e5 or c5. We also have the option of exchanging the bishops by playing Bb7 at any time we like. }
12. O-O Rd8 { e5 is a serious threat now; so is Qd6. } 13. Rfd1 Qd6
{ Making the bishop move so that we have the option of playing c5 and getting rid of our doubled pawns. }
14. Bg2 c5 { With a lot of simplifications to follow in the center. } 15. d5
exd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Qxd5 18. Bxd5 Be6
{ A rook endgame is a convenient outcome for Black, as we know the drawish tendency they possess. }
19. Bxe6 fxe6 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Rc1 Rd2
{ With a completely equal rook endgame due to our very active rook on d2 and White's vulnerable pawns on e2, b2 and a2. }
