{ This natural move has been played the most, but it already gives away the advantage because it gives Black time to defend the pawn on c4 by bringing the knight from f6 to b6. }
9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. f4 { This allows us to breathe! } 11... O-O 12. O-O
Rb8
{ Now we are in time to play b5 and follow up with Bb7. These kinds of positions are very tricky. They might look passive, but the slightest inaccuracy by White, and we'll just be a pawn up and have a winning position! If White tries to stop b5 by playing a4, we can fix the weak b4-square by playing a5 and continue with b6, Bb7, while keeping the Qb4 possibility in mind. }
