[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3
{ The main move. White has some other options as well. We examine them in the corresponding chapters. }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nc6
{ An interesting move which has become very fashionable lately. It feels a bit strange to develop the knight in front of the c7-pawn, but it has its purpose: to take the e5-square away from the knight on f3! We also threaten Ne4 followed by Qb4+, so White should do something about it. }
7. Nc3 d5
{ White has a few possibilities here:   8.cxd5  claiming that they have an advantage due to our strangely placed knight on c6 in a Carlsbad structure.   8.Ne5  , forcing Black to take with  8...dxc4  , then take on  9.Nxc6  , and continue by playing against our spoiled pawn structure.   Play  8.Bg2  to continue the development, allowing us to take on  8...dxc4  but gaining space in the center in return, and thus attempt to claim the advantage due to our difficulties in finishing our development on the queenside. }
8. Bg2 dxc4 9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7
{ White now has doubled pawns, too and our pawn majority on the queenside has grown even more: 4:2. The problems we face in return are the lack of control over the d-file and the difficulty of developing our c8-bishop. Things are not as sad as they seem though! }
11. Qd4 Nb6 12. O-O Rb8
{ We defend the pawn on b7, preparing to develop our bishop to d7 and then maybe to c6. }
13. a4 { White tries to destabilize our knight on b6. } 13... a5
{ Fixing White's pawn structure on the queenside and gaining an important square: b4. }
14. Nb5 O-O 15. Na3
{ Here we can see the downside of White's earlier a4. We can now always defend our c4-pawn by playing Qb4. Another important thing to keep in mind is that, even if White gets back their pawn by winning the one on c4, we will still have a better pawn structure due to their doubled e-pawns.   All the endgames will be better for us because we would play as if we were a pawn up! The only thing we should make sure to do is to take advantage of the time White spends on winning the c4-pawn and finish our development, ideally by exchanging the bishops too. }
15... Rd8 16. Qc3 Qb4
{ As said before: all endgames are convenient for Black! Now another problem arising in White's position is the weak a4-pawn, especially after we play Bd7. Black is slightly better. }
