[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Bogo-Indian 4.Bd2 Qe7 5.g3"]
[Black "8.Bg2 dxc4 9.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ White has a few possibilities here:  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  4.Nbd2  and  4.Nc3  , which transposes to a Nimzo with the Nf3-setup. Let's start with the mainline! }
4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3
{ The main move. White has some other options as well. We examine them in the corresponding chapters. }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nc6
{ An interesting move which has become very fashionable lately. It feels a bit strange to develop the knight in front of the c7-pawn, but it has its purpose: to take the e5-square away from the knight on f3! We also threaten Ne4 followed by Qb4+, so White should do something about it. }
7. Nc3 d5
{ White has a few possibilities here:   8.cxd5  claiming that they have an advantage due to our strangely placed knight on c6 in a Carlsbad structure.   8.Ne5  , forcing Black to take with  8...dxc4  , then take on  9.Nxc6  , and continue by playing against our spoiled pawn structure.   Play  8.Bg2  to continue the development, allowing us to take on  8...dxc4  but gaining space in the center in return, and thus attempt to claim the advantage due to our difficulties in finishing our development on the queenside. }
8. Bg2 dxc4 9. O-O { The only way for White to play for an advantage! } 9...
O-O 10. Ne5
{ We intended to play Rd8 followed by e5, that's why White plays Ne5 themselves. }
10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7
{ White must defend their e5-pawn. It gives us enough time to organize some counterplay. }
12. Qd4 Qc5
{ Exchanging the queens is almost always a relief in a position with little space. White cannot avoid it, as the pawn on e5 will fall otherwise. }
13. Qxc5 Nxc5
{ White has good compensation for the sacrificed pawn, as the bishop on g2 is a monster and we will have some difficulties finishing the development on the queenside. Black must be very precise here to avoid getting in trouble.  14.Rfc1  will transpose to the mainline after  14...Rb8  15.Nb5  Bd7  . }
14. Nb5
{ White plays this move not only to attack c7 but also to stop us from defending the c4-pawn with a6, Rb8 and b5. }
14... Rb8
{ An invitation for White to take some poisoned pawns!  15.Nxa7  will be met by  15...c6  and the knight is trapped. If @@StartFEN@@1rb2rk1/ppp2ppp/4p3/1Nn1P3/2p5/6P1/PP2PPBP/R4RK1 w - - 2 15@@EndFEN@@15.  Nxc7  then  15...Bd7  and the knight is stuck again. }
15. Rac1
{ This perfectly logical move is already an inaccuracy. Why? Because later in the variation, when we take with the bishop on b5 and then on e2, the rook on f1 will be hanging. That's why White should play Rfc1 instead. }
15... Bd7 { Once again, our a7- and c7-pawns are untouchable! } 16. Rxc4 Bxb5
17. Rxc5 Bxe2
{ Compared to the variation with Rfc1, White loses a tempo here. } 18. Re1 Bh5
{ The bishop must control the d1-square to ensure that we will be the one to occupy the d-file. }
19. Rxc7 Rfd8 { Now the d-file is ours! } 20. Bxb7 Rd2
{ Once again, the pawns on the second rank become vulnerable. } 21. Re3 g5
{ Gaining space on the kingside and, at the same time, securing our king. Black has enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn due to the fantastic rook we have on d2, which both attacks the b2- and a2-pawns and also eyes White's weak king. White doesn't have enough resources to both keep their material advantage and secure their king. }
*

