[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Bogo-Indian 6. Qxd2 d6  (Alternative)"]
[Black "10.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 d6
{ The alternative to  6...Nc6  . Black goes for the typical setup with O-O and e5. }
7. Nc3 O-O 8. Bg2
{ White does their best to finish their development as fast as possible. } 8...
e5 { We need to open up our bishop! } 9. O-O Re8
{ Preparing e4 followed by e3. White needs to decide what to do about the pawn structure in the center. There are quite a few options... }
10. e3 { White wants to recapture on d4 with the pawn. } 10... a5
{ A useful move that stops a potential pawn expansion on the queenside. } 11.
b3
{ White is preparing the pawn expansion anyway. They want to go for a3 and b4. }
11... e4 { The time has come for us to close up everything in the center. } 12.
Ng5 Bf5
{ The e4-pawn is well protected and we threaten to play 13 ... h6 and maybe even 14...g5, limiting White's knight to h3. }
13. f3 { The only way for White to stop our h6/g5-idea. } 13... exf3 14. Bxf3
{ The pawn on b7 is hanging now. } 14... c6 15. e4 Bg6 16. Rae1
{ White has tried to place all of their pieces on their optimal squares. }
16... Nbd7
{ And so did Black. Our position might be more passive, but there are actually a lot of dangers to White's over-expanded pawn structure. If any of White's pawns advance, they might become a target! Our plan is to make solid moves, while we wait for that to happen - eventually White will lose their patience. Meanwhile, we can bring the d7-knight to e6 to exchange one more light piece. Or, if White prevents it, we can continue with c5, weakening White's dark squares in the center. }
