[White "10. Catalan Bogo-Indian 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.g3 "]
[Black "4.Nd2 with 6.Qc2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3
{ This move order is actually intended to avoid the Queen's Indian  3.Nf3  b6  . It doesn't, however, do much harm if we intend to go for the Bogo. After  3...Bb4+  , we will mostly transpose to the previously examined lines. There is one exception that we're going to examine here. }
3... Bb4+
{ Now  4.Bd2  will eventually transpose to the previously examined lines. } 4.
Nd2
{ This is the only setup where we intended to go for the b6-plan, but we don't have time for it now:  4...b6  will be met by  5.Bg2  and Black might get in trouble. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. Qc2
{ The only way to avoid the transposition to the 4. Nbd2 lines, but with the disadvantage that White will be behind in development. }
6... c5 { That means we can start some activity in the center! } 7. dxc5 Nc6
{ Threatening 8... Nd4. } 8. cxd5 { White tries to keep their extra c5-pawn. }
8... exd5 9. Nf3 Qe7
{ Because of the pinned d2-knight, White isn't able to protect their extra pawn. }
10. O-O Bxc5
{ Despite our isolated pawn, the position is good for us, as White doesn't have control over the d4-square @@StartBracket@@their knight is not well-placed on d2, it would much rather be on c3@@EndBracket@@. We'll follow up with developing the bishop to g4 and then the a-rook will come to c8. If White tries to fix our isolated pawn with e3, we can just get rid of it by playing d4.     If White plays the tempting  11.Nb3  the knight's position is still not ideal. Black just retreats with  11...Bb6  If White continues with the logical  12.Bg5  , we play  12...h6  13.Bxf6  Qxf6  , gaining the bishop pair and a small advantage, as the position has an open character and White's knights are not attacking Black's isolated pawn. Black can then continue with Bf5, Rd8 and d4. }
