{ Now  4.Bd2  will eventually transpose to the previously examined lines. } 4.
Bd2
{ One might want to pay attention to the move order we choose here to transpose to the 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 line. }
4... Qe7 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. e3
{ White tries to avoid the transposition to the mainlines by delaying the development of the g1-knight. }
6... e5 7. dxe5
{ This doesn't pose Black any problems, as we'll be in time to castle and then play d5. }
7... Nxe5
{ The c4-pawn is now hanging and White has to lose another tempo to protect it. }
8. Qc2 O-O 9. Ne2 Rd8
{ Preparing to play d5. White doesn't have a good way to stop it, as  10.Nc3  is not possible because the c4-pawn would be hanging, while  10.e4  might be met by either the immediate  10...d5  followed by c6 with a nice counterplay after any capture, or by  10...c6  preparing d5. }
10. O-O Bxd2 11. Nxd2 d5
{ With a solid position. Black will play c6 to limit White's strong, fianchettoed bishop. Then Black will either develop their own bishop to g4, if possible, or go for ideas with Nb4 to exploit the somewhat vulnerable d3-square  (e.g. after a pawn exchange on d5)  . }
