[White "10. Catalan Bogo-Indian 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.g3 "]
[Black "3.g3 Bb4+ 4.Bd2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3
{ This move order is actually intended to avoid the Queen's Indian  3.Nf3  b6  . It doesn't, however, do much harm if we intend to go for the Bogo. After  3...Bb4+  , we will mostly transpose to the previously examined lines. There is one exception that we're going to examine here. }
3... Bb4+
{ Now  4.Bd2  will eventually transpose to the previously examined lines. } 4.
Bd2
{ One might want to pay attention to the move order we choose here to transpose to the 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 line. }
4... Qe7 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. e3
{ White tries to avoid the transposition to the mainlines by delaying the development of the g1-knight. }
6... e5
{ Taking advantage of the fact that White's knight is not controlling the e5-square yet. }
7. d5 Bxd2+ 8. Nxd2 Nb8
{ Heading to the very similar King's Indian structures, where Black's typical plan to develop the pieces is d6, O-O, a6 , Nbd7@@StartBracket@@Na6@@EndBracket@@-Nc5. }
9. Ne2
{ That's the whole point of White's delaying the development of the g1-knight until the last moment! We can see now that the knight wouldn't do much on f3 because his friend is already on d2, meaning that they would both fight for the same squares. It's much better placed on e2, as both knights have their own squares. }
9... d6 10. Nc3 O-O 11. O-O { Both sides continue their development. } 11... a5
{ A typical move to secure the c5-square for the b8-knight and to stop White's pawn expansion on the queenside. }
12. a3 { White doesn't give up on the b4-idea so easily though! } 12... Na6
{ Even though it's at the side of the board, this is the best place for Black's knight, because it would get in the way of the c8-bishop if it was on d7 instead. }
13. b4
{ White takes advantage of the potential pin on the a-file.  13...axb4  would be met by  14.axb4  , where Black's knight can't capture the b4-pawn due to the pin. }
13... Bf5 { Black develops the last piece and threatens to take on b4. } 14. e4
Bd7
{ The best square for the bishop, as it supports ideas on both of the flanks from here. }
15. Qb3 { Protecting the b4-pawn and planning to prepare c5 next. } 15... axb4
16. axb4 c5
{ Not allowing White to even think of playing c5. Closing the queenside would be convenient for Black, as it would allow us to focus on our counterplay on the kingside. Note that a plan with h5-h4 would be very effective, as White's knight isn't placed on f3, from where it would guard the h4-square. If White meets h5 with h4, ideas with Ng4 @@StartBracket@@or Nh7@@EndBracket@@, followed by g5 come to mind.   If White plays  17.dxc6  ,  the b4-pawn  might become a target after  17...bxc6  and  18.--  Rfb8  will be a serious threat. }
