[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3
{ This move order is actually intended to avoid the Queen's Indian  3.Nf3  b6  . It doesn't, however, do much harm if we intend to go for the Bogo. After  3...Bb4+  , we will mostly transpose to the previously examined lines. There is one exception that we're going to examine here. }
3... Bb4+
{ Now  4.Bd2  will eventually transpose to the previously examined lines. } 4.
Bd2
{ One might want to pay attention to the move order we choose here to transpose to the 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 line. }
4... Qe7 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. e3
{ White tries to avoid the transposition to the mainlines by delaying the development of the g1-knight. }
6... e5
{ Taking advantage of the fact that White's knight is not controlling the e5-square yet. }
7. d5 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 Nb8 9. d6 { White wants to bury Black's bishop on c8. }
9... Qxd6 { It will be easier to solve the c8-bishop problem in the endgame. }
10. Qxd6 cxd6 11. Nc3
{ It is clear that White has good compensation for the sacrificed pawn, as the d6-pawn is weak and so are the d5- and b5-squares. The bishop on c8 doesn't have great prospects either. But don't worry - we have a way to solve these problems, one by one. }
11... Na6 12. Nb5 Ke7
{ White got distracted from controlling the d5-square and Black will be happy to return the extra pawn to solve the problems of the weak d5-square and the buried bishop. }
13. Ne2 d5 14. cxd5 d6
