[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Zdenko Kozul vs. Mladen Palac, Opatija 2012"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nc6 7. Nc3 d5
{ It seems to me that the Croatians were the ones who brought this variation to the attention of the broader public. GM Kozul became the first 'victim'! }
8. Ne5 dxc4 9. Bg2 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. f4
{ 11.Qd4  Is the best continuation. We also examine it here in the course. }
11... O-O 12. O-O-O
{ GM Kozul is known for his aggressive chess!   12.O-O  Rb8  And Black keeps the extra pawn. }
12... Nb6 13. h4 { White is consistent: He wants to attack on the kingside. }
13... Rb8
{ Preparing to finally develop the bishop now that the b7-pawn is protected. }
14. h5 Bd7 15. h6 g6 16. Ne4
{ White spots the weak f6-square and goes for it. } 16... Ba4
{ Black starts his own attack on the queenside. } 17. Nf6+ Kh8 18. Rdg1 Rfd8
{ Occupying the open d-file and bringing one more piece into the attack! } 19.
Qa5 Rd4
{ c3 might be a threat to keep in mind, as taking with the queen runs into a nasty pin: Rc4. }
20. Ne4
{ 20.Kb1  It might have been better to bring the king to a safer place... }
20... Bc6
{ 20...c3!  would have been really beautiful and effective. There is a very subtle follow-up after White's 21. Nxc3.  21.Nxc3   21.bxc3??  Qa3+  22.Kb1  Rxe4  23.Bxe4  Bc2+-+   21.Qxc3??  Rc4-+  a6!!  with the idea 22... Rb4 and 23... Nc4, trapping White's queen.  22.Nxa4?  Rxa4-+ }
21. Qc5 { White hopes that the endgame will save the game! } 21... Qxc5 22.
Nxc5 Bxg2 23. Rxg2 Nd5
{ It turns out that the endgame is also much better for Black, as White's pawn majority on the kingside has difficulties moving, while Black's on the queenside will advance. }
24. Rf2 b6 25. Na4 Rd8
{ Black also has control over the only open file on the board. } 26. Rf3 Kg8
{ In endgames, the king should move closer to the center. } 27. Re1 f5
{ Fixing White's kingside pawns forever! } 28. Nc3
{ 28.exf6  Nxf6-+  White has too many weaknesses. } 28... Nxc3
{ Going for the rook endgame is risky, as we know that they have a high drawing tendency.   28...Nb4-+  Keeping the knights on the board would have been better. }
29. Rxc3 c5 30. e3 Rd2 31. Rxc4 Rg2 32. Rc2
{ 32.Rc3!  Rxg3  33.Ra3  33...a5  34.Rb3  would give White very high drawing chances. }
32... Rxg3 33. b4 Rh3
{ 33...cxb4  34.Rc7  White intends to activate the rook and keep good drawing chances. }
34. bxc5 bxc5 35. Rxc5 Rxh6 36. Rc7 a5 37. Re2 Rh1+ 38. Kb2 Rhd1 39. Re7 Rb8+
40. Ka3
{ A big blunder.   40.Kc2  Ra1  41.Kd3=  would keep the position balanced. }
40... Rb4 { Now the poor white king finds himself in a mating net! } 41. Rb2
Rd3+ 42. Rb3 Rbxb3+ 43. axb3 Rxe3 { This endgame is totally winning! } 44. Rxe6
Re4 45. Ra6 Rxf4 46. Rxa5 Re4 47. b4 f4 48. b5 Rxe5 49. Kb4 f3 50. b6 Re1 51.
Ra3 f2 52. b7 f1=Q 53. b8=Q+ Qf8+
{ Despite a good amount of adventures, Black has managed to win the game, mostly thanks to the big advantage he got out of the opening! One can notice how players with an aggressive style might find it difficult to play against the Bogo. }
