[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Evgeny Postny vs. David Navara"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nc6 7. Nc3 d5 8.
cxd5 exd5
{ GM Postny chooses a more solid approach, trying to exploit the misplaced knight on c6, which has served its purpose @@StartBracket@@in his attempt, White took the pressure off in the center and opened Black's passive c8-bishop@@EndBracket@@. Black will have to find a better position for it, for example on d7, from where it allows him to bolster his pawn chain with c6. }
9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O h6
{ Black could develop his bishop to f5 immediately.   10...Bf5!?  11.Nh4  GM Navara probably disliked this knight move and that's why he chose to play 10... h6 instead - so that he could retreat his bishop to h7.  11...Be6=  But Black's bishop would be fine on e6 as well. }
11. Rac1 Bf5 { Completing the development and planning Ne4. } 12. Rfd1 Ne4 13.
Qf4 Nxc3 14. Rxc3 Be4 15. Ne5
{ 15.Rdc1+=  Would have assured White some advantage thanks to the misplaced knight on c6. Because the c7-pawn is also weak, it would have been difficult for Black to reroute the knight to a better position. }
15... Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Nxe5 17. Qxe5 Qxe5 18. dxe5 c6
{ The rook endgame is still a bit more pleasant for White, but with precise play, Black should comfortably hold. We already know some ideas from our mainline. For example, here. }
19. e4 { A good move, trying to activate the rooks at all costs! } 19... dxe4
20. Rd7 Rab8 21. Rb3 a5
{ Moving the a-pawn away from any potential danger on the 7th rank. } 22. Rbxb7
Rxb7 23. Rxb7 Rd8
{ Black activates his rook as well, which ensures him enough counterplay. } 24.
Kf1 Rd2 25. h4 g6 26. a4 h5 27. Rb6 Rc2
{ 27...Kf8  Perhaps it would have been easier to just ignore the threat of Rxc6 and bring the king to the center!  28.Rxc6  Rxb2  29.Ra6  Ke7  30.Rxa5  Ke6=  With a totally drawn position. White can't make any progress. }
28. b4 { White finds a nice chance! } 28... Rc4
{ 28...axb4!?  29.Rxb4  Winning a pawn, though it still would be a very long way to victory @@StartBracket@@if it's at all possible to win@@EndBracket@@. }
29. bxa5 Rxa4 30. a6 c5 31. Ke2 Ra3
{ Not allowing White's king to come any closer to the e4-pawn. } 32. Kd2 c4 33.
Kc1 c3 34. Kc2 Kf8 35. Rb8+ Kg7 36. Rb6 Kf8 37. Rc6 Kg8 38. Rd6 Kf8 39. Rb6 Kg8
{ 39...Ke7=  not allowing e6. } 40. Kb1 Kg7 41. Rc6 Kf8 42. Rf6 Ke8
{ 42...Ke7= } 43. e6 fxe6 44. Rxg6 Rxa6 45. Rg5 Rb6+ 46. Kc2 Rb2+ 47. Kxc3 Rxf2
48. Rxh5 Rf3+ 49. Kd4 Rxg3 50. Kxe4
{ In this game we can see that the positions we get from the Bogo are very, very solid. Even after so many inaccuracies, Black could hold the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Ivan Sokolov vs. Nikita Vitiugov, Antalya 2013"]
[Result "*"]

{ The Bogo-Indian has been in the repertoire of GM Vitiugov for many years and it has served him very well! }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nc6 7. Nc3 d5 8.
Ne5 dxc4 9. Nxc6 bxc6 { Going for a Catalan-like pawn structure. } 10. Bg2 O-O
11. Qc2
{ White prophylactically moves the queen away from the potential x-ray on the d-file, while the queen is also eyeing the c4-pawn and protecting the b2-pawn. }
11... Rb8 { Preparing c5. } 12. O-O { 12.Bxc6  runs into  12...Qd6  . } 12...
c5 13. Rfd1 cxd4 14. Rxd4 Qb4
{ A multi-purpose move: it both defends the c4-pawn and attacks the one on b2. }
15. Rd2 Ba6
{ Black prefers to keep the bishops on the board, protecting the extra c4-pawn and planning to put pressure on the weak b2-pawn. }
16. Rad1 Rb6 { Preparing to triple on the b-file. } 17. Na4 Rd6
{ What a nice rook maneuver! White can't trade rooks, as that would undouble Black's pawns. }
18. a3 Rxd2 19. Rxd2 Qa5 20. Nc3 g6 21. Qa4
{ White gives up on the hope of creating counterplay and is looking for drawish chances in the endgame instead.   21.Ne4  Nxe4  22.Bxe4  See how useful g6 was? h7 is not attacked now!  22...Kg7=+ }
21... Qxa4 22. Nxa4 Rb8
{ Black has an extra pawn but, because it's doubled, converting it is not going to be easy! }
23. Kf1 Kf8
{ Both sides know that the king should come to the center in the endgame. } 24.
Ke1 Bb5 25. Nc3 Ba6
{ 'Teasing' White. I suspect Black didn't really want to go for a repetition in case White plays the knight back to e4. Sometimes it is useful to give your opponent a choice. }
26. h3 { 26.Na4  Ke7=+ } 26... Ke7 27. f4 Nd7
{ The knight wasn't doing much on f6 and Black correctly decides to find a better place for it. }
28. Kd1
{ 28.Na4  It was important for White not to allow Black's knight to the active c5-square!  28...Nb6  29.Nc5  Bb5=+  Black is better, but converting it to a full point won't be an easy job... }
28... Nc5 29. Kc2 h6
{ Black intends to create the second weakness in White's camp by playing g5. }
30. h4 h5 31. a4
{ White probably didn't like the prospect of a long defense and went immediately wrong. The a4-pawn is now also weak. }
31... Rb6 { 31...Bb7  32.Bxb7  Rxb7  33.Rd4  Rb4-+  would win another pawn! }
32. a5 Rd6 { 32...Rb4-+  Why not go for the a5-pawn with Nb3-a5? } 33. Ne4
Rxd2+ 34. Kxd2
{ 34.Nxd2!  Nb3  35.Nxb3  cxb3+  36.Kd2=  would most likely have held the draw!   36.Kxb3?  Bxe2∓  Keeping the winning chances. }
34... Nb3+ 35. Kc3 Bb7
{ 35...Nxa5?!  36.Nc5  Activating the pieces as much as possible, thus keeping high drawing chances. }
36. a6
{ 36.Kxc4  would have been better.  36...Nxa5+  37.Kb4  Nc6+  38.Kc5  Nb8∓ }
36... Bxa6 { Two extra pawns are more than enough now! } 37. Nf2 Nc1 38. Bf3
Na2+ 39. Kd4 c3
{ Giving away one of the pawns, but creating a healthy passer! } 40. bxc3 c5+
41. Kxc5 Nxc3 42. Nd3
{ This loses on the spot.   42.e4  Be2-+  would only prolong the suffering. }
42... Bxd3 43. exd3 a5 44. d4
{ 44.Kc4  Nd5-+  Going for the weak g3-pawn. After  45.Bxd5  exd5  46.Kxd5  f5  the endgame would be lost for White due to Black's advanced passed a-pawn. }
44... f5 45. Kc4 Ne4 46. Kb5 Kd6 47. Kxa5 Kd5 48. Kb5 Kxd4 49. Kc6 Ke3
{ A very nice game by GM Vitiugov! One can see how easy it is for White to go wrong when unfamiliar with this line. All Black needs to do is solve the problem of the c8-bishop and then try to go for an endgame, where the extra pawn @@StartBracket@@even if doubled@@EndBracket@@ matters a lot. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Frank James Marshall vs Jose Raul Capablanca, Berlin 1928"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Nc3 b6 6. e3 Bxc3
{ In the course we don't hurry with this move, preferring 6... Bb7, where we wait for White to lose a tempo with a3 and only then take on c3.   6...Bb7  7.Bd3  O-O  8.O-O  d6  9.a3  Bxc3  See the 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Nc3 line }
7. Bxc3 Ne4
{ Still, the plan here is quite similar to what we've seen throughout the course: take control over the e4-square, then prepare either d6, e5 or f5 with an attack on the kingside. }
8. Rc1 Bb7 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O d6
{ Capablanca plans to finish his development with Nd7. } 11. Nd2
{ Trying to get rid of Black's best piece: the knight on e4.   11.Be1!?  It was better to keep the dark-squared bishop by retreating it to e1 and only then play Nd2.  11...Nd7  12.Nd2+= }
11... Nxc3
{ Taking the bishop, of course, and not allowing White to keep his bishop pair. }
12. Rxc3 c5
{ Black has equalized comfortably, as he managed to trade some light pieces, assuring he has enough space for the remaining ones to maneuver around. }
13. dxc5
{ White takes off the pressure in the center too early.   13.d5!?  exd5  14.cxd5  Na6   14...Bxd5??  15.Qh5±  15.e4  would lead to a complicated but balanced Benoni-like structure. }
13... dxc5
{ White's pieces are very strangely placed, especially the rook on c3... Marshall probably realized he was not in time to get control over the recently opened d-file and tries an attack on the kingside. }
14. Qh5
{ 14.Qc2  wouldn't be better.  14...f5!  Closing in White's 'battery' and planning to continue with Nc6, followed by e5-e4. Black has a clear advantage, as he's the only one really playing. White doesn't have any good counterplay. }
14... h6 15. f4
{ White tries to make f5-f6 happen fast, so as to open up Black's king. } 15...
Nd7 { Aiming for the f6-square and finishing the development. } 16. e4
{ White wants to play e5 first, not allowing Capablanca's knight to f6, and only then f5.   16.f5?  Nf6  17.Qe2  exf5  18.Bxf5  Rfe8∓  with a big advantage for Black thanks to the superior pawn structure and the weakness of the e3-pawn. }
16... e5
{ The former World Champion doesn't allow White to bring his plan to life. If 17. f5, the bishop on d3 will be a very sad piece. }
17. Nf3 Rae8
{ Trying to get White to play f5 and close up his d3-bishop for good. } 18. Nh4
{ 18.f5  Nf6  Double attack!  19.Qh4  The only way to both defend the e4-pawn and save the queen.  19...Nxe4!  A little tactic!  20.Bxe4  Qxh4  21.Nxh4  Bxe4∓  winning a pawn. }
18... exf4 19. Rxf4 Qg5
{ All of White's pieces could not be placed any worse! } 20. Qf3 Ne5 21. Qf2
Nxd3 22. Rxd3 Rxe4 { Winning a nice central pawn. } 23. Rxe4 Bxe4 24. Re3 f5
{ An extra pawn and a fantastic bishop. Both are good reasons for Black's strategy to triumph! }
25. h3 Rd8 { Occupying the open file. } 26. a3 Rd1+ 27. Kh2 Qf6 28. Qf4
{ Desperation. } 28... g5 29. Rg3 Kf8 30. Qb8+ Rd8 31. Qe5 Qxe5 32. Ng6+ Kf7
33. Nxe5+ Kf6
{ The knight is lost, because if  34.Nf3  then  34...f4  35.Rg4  Bf5  and the rook is trapped. This game illustrates how easily things can go wrong for White if they ignore the positional principles of the game and instead, try to go all-in with an attack on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nana Dzagnidze . vs. Ju Wenjun, Tehran 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Nc3 b6 6. e3 Bb7 7. Be2
{ In our lines we analyze the 7. Bd3-move, which gives White a better version of the position that appears in the game. }
7... O-O 8. O-O d6 9. Rc1
{ With the bishop on d3 instead of e2, it would have been much easier for White to prepare e4. }
9... Bxc3
{ Perhaps a bit too early...   9...c5  Waiting for White to play a3 and only then taking on c3.  10.a3  Bxc3  11.Bxc3  Ne4  12.Be1  e5  13.d5  f5∞  With a complicated position where each side would have their play: Black on the kingside and White on the queenside. }
10. Bxc3 Ne4 11. Qc2
{ It would have been better for White to keep the bishop pair.   11.Be1  Nd7  12.Nd2  Trading Black's most active piece!  12...Nxd2  13.Qxd2+=  With a small advantage for White due to the bishop pair and some extra space. }
11... Nd7
{ 11...Nxc3!  If White allows the trade, one shouldn't miss the chance!  12.Qxc3  Nd7  13.b4  a5=  With a balanced position. If  14.a3  , Black can always take on b4, opening up the a-line with good play. }
12. Rfd1
{ White allows the trade on c3 once again... She intends to bring the rook into the game and only then retreat the bishop to e1. }
12... f5
{ I'm sure GM Ju Wenjun knew that taking on c3 was the best way to equalize, but perhaps she wanted to play for a win by keeping as many pieces on the board as possible.   12...Nxc3  13.Qxc3  a5= }
13. Be1 a5
{ As we already know, this is a very useful move that fights against the b4-idea. }
14. Nd2 { White tries to exchange Black's good knight on e4. } 14... Nxd2 15.
Qxd2 e5 16. f3
{ 16.dxe5?  Nxe5  17.f3  Rae8=+  With a better pawn structure and a better position thanks to the weakness on e3. }
16... Rae8
{ X-raying the e2-bishop and threatening to win a pawn with 17... exd4.   16...f4!?  Could have lead to an interesting pawn structure.  17.exf4  exd4  18.Bf2  18...c5  With a highly unclear position, but Black should have good play thanks to the super-strong d4-pawn and the weak f4-pawn, which can be attacked by Qf6. }
17. Bf1 Qg5 { The pawn on f3 is now hanging. } 18. d5
{ It is a mistake to take the pressure off in the center. Black won't have to worry about c5 anytime soon and can just focus on her kingside attack.  18.Kh1  Moving away from the pin would have been much better, as Black's attack is not as dangerous as it might look. At the same time, c5 is a serious threat!  18...Qh5!?  Leaving the potential f4-fork so that after  19.c5  , Black can take  19...dxc5  and after  20.dxe5  Nxe5  all is fine.  The position remains complicated, with Black having to make sure the c5-breakthrough won't ever work, while also trying to create threats on the kingside.   18...Rf6?  19.c5!  bxc5   19...dxc5  20.dxe5  20...Nxe5  21.f4+-  20.Qxa5  Rh6  21.Qxc7  Qh5  22.h4+-  There is no mate and in the meantime, the whole of Black's queenside has collapsed... }
18... h5 19. b3
{ White will now slowly prepare b4.   19.a3?  a4=+  Now b4 will never happen. }
19... h4 20. a3
{ 20.h3  It was necessary to stop Black from playing h3 herself.  20...Qh5  21.Qf2  g5  22.c5  bxc5   22...dxc5?  23.d6±  Opening up the position for White's rooks and the bishop pair.   22...Nxc5  23.a3  With a very unpleasant position for Black due to the weak c7-pawn.  23.Bxa5  With good counterplay on the queenside. }
20... h3 21. g3 { White's kingside becomes weaker and weaker... } 21... Qh5 22.
Be2 g5
{ 22...Nf6!?  Tempting White to play 23. b4.  23.b4  c5!  24.bxa5  bxa5  25.Qxa5  e4-+  It is impossible to protect f3 now.  26.Kf2?  exf3  27.Bxf3  Ng4+-+ }
23. b4 axb4 24. axb4 g4
{ Perhaps a bit premature.   24...Nf6=+  Targeting the d5-pawn, so that White cannot play c5 easily, while also making sure to control the e4-square, so that after 25... g4, there is no 26. f4-option for White. }
25. f4 { White has almost succeeded in stabilizing her kingside. } 25... Qf7
26. Ra1 Ra8
{ 26...Nf6  It was very important to take control over the e4-square first!  27.Ra7  is not dangerous in view of  27...Bc8  . }
27. fxe5
{ 27.e4!  White missed her chance to counterattack!  27...Rxa1   27...fxe4??  28.Rxa8  Rxa8  29.Bxg4+-   27...exf4  28.Qxf4±  Black's pawns are now very vulnerable.  28.Rxa1  exf4  29.Qxf4  Qg7  30.Rc1  Qe5  Perhaps Black could try to hold a position like this... }
27... Nxe5 { The knight has landed on its dream square! } 28. Qd4 b5
{ Trying to attack White's central pawn chain as fast as possible.   28...Rxa1  It would have been better to first trade rooks, which would leave the d5-pawn with one less defender.  29.Rxa1  b5=+ }
29. cxb5
{ 29.Rxa8!  Rxa8  30.c5  The pawn is now protected enough times.  30...Ra2  31.Kf1  This position remains complicated, with all results being possible here. }
29... Rxa1
{ 29...Qxd5!  would have been more precise!  30.Qxd5+  Bxd5  31.Rxa8  Bxa8-+  With an extra pawn and a totally winning position. Pay attention to White's completely ruined pawn structure... }
30. Rxa1 { Now White at least has some counterplay on the a-file. } 30... Bxd5
31. Bc3 Bf3 32. Bf1 Be4 33. Kf2 Qb3 34. Be2 Qc2 35. Qd2
{ 35.Rd1  The only way to try holding the game!  35...Ra8   35...Nd3+??  36.Rxd3+-   35...Bf3  36.Rd2  36.Rd2  Qc1  37.Rd1  And it's unclear how Black should progress. }
35... Qxd2 36. Bxd2 Bf3 { 36...Bd3-+  would have forced the trade. } 37. Bf1
Bd5 38. Be2 Bf3 39. Bf1 Be4
{ Perhaps the players were in time trouble just before move 40 and that is why Black repeated the position a few times. }
40. Be2 Bd3 { Finally the right idea! } 41. Bc3 Bxe2 42. Bxe5
{ 42.Kxe2  would be completely lost due to the weak h2-pawn.  42...Nf3  43.Rh1  Ra8-+ }
42... Bxb5 43. Bd4 Rc8
{ Despite the opposite-colored bishops, Black's position is winning thanks to the extra pawn and White's weak king and h2-pawn. One can just lay back now and enjoy the technique of the Women's World Champion! }
44. Ra5 Bd3 45. Ke1 Kf7 { Bringing the king to the center. } 46. Kd2 Be4 47.
Kc3 Ke6 48. Kc4 Bf3 49. Kc3 Be2 50. Kd2 Bf1 51. Kc3 c6 52. Ba7 Bb5 53. Kd4 Re8
54. Ra2 Kd7 55. Kc3 Re4 56. Rc2 Re5 57. Bd4 Re8 58. Ba7 Ra8 59. Ra2 c5 60. Ra3
Rc8 61. Bb6 Kc6 62. Ba5 Re8 63. Kd2 f4 64. gxf4 g3 65. hxg3 Bf1 66. Ke1 h2 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Benjamin Gledura vs. Rustam Kasimdzhanov, Budapest 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7 7. e3 O-O 8.
Be2 d5 { The same line which is recommended in the course. } 9. b3 Nbd7
{ This is what I like about the Bogo: everything is very logical. Just develop your pieces, fight for the center, etc. ... It's very difficult to go wrong when following the basic chess principles. }
10. O-O c5 11. Bb2 Qe7
{ In the course, I recommend to start with 11... Rc8, but there isn't anything wrong with GM Kasimdzhanov's choice either.   11...Rc8  12.Rac1  Ne4  See the 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 line. }
12. Rfd1 Rfd8 13. Rac1 Rac8
{ Both sides harmoniously finished their development. Now it's time to maneuver around! }
14. Qe1
{ With this move White probably just wanted to move his queen away from the x-ray on the d-file. }
14... h6
{ Creating 'luft' for the king. This loses a bit of time, but my guess is that Black just didn't want to be the one to initiate massive simplifications.   14...dxc4!?  15.Bxc4  15...Bxf3  16.gxf3  cxd4  17.Rxd4  h6∞  With a complicated but balanced position. White has the bishop pair, but his pawn structure is spoiled and the king is weakened. Black can bring his d7-knight to g6, preparing an attack on the kingside. }
15. dxc5
{ White finds the right moment to open up the position a bit for his bishops. }
15... Nxc5 16. b4 Nce4
{ Black's problem now is that both of his knights will fight for the same squares... Ideally, he should have avoided this. }
17. Ne5 dxc4 { It's not possible to avoid the simplifications any longer. } 18.
Nxc4 Rxd1 19. Rxd1 Bd5 20. Rc1
{ White has a small advantage here thanks to the bishop pair. It is very interesting to see how, from this point onwards, GM Kasimdzhanov slowly outplayed his less experienced opponent. }
20... Bxc4
{ Black tries to create an imbalance: two knights against two bishops! } 21.
Bxc4 Rd8 22. f3
{ This is already an inaccuracy. As mentioned before, Black's knights are struggling and there is no need to help them find better routes. White probably just wanted to cover the g4-square with a tempo @@StartBracket@@Black was threatening 22... Ng4@@EndBracket@@.   22.Be2  would have been better, planning to exchange the heavy pieces with 23. Rd1 - an endgame with two bishops against two knights would be a dream for White! }
22... Nd6 23. Bb3 { White couldn't allow the trade. } 23... Nf5
{ Black's knights are now much better placed than before! } 24. e4
{ Another inaccuracy. White shouldn't have weakened the d4-square. With  24.Qf2+=  he could have prevented Black from playing Nd4 after e4. }
24... Nd4
{ Only two inaccuracies by White - that's all Black needed to solve his problems! The knight on d4 is now a 'monster'. }
25. e5
{ White probably senses that his opponent's strategic skills are superior, so he tries to change the character of the game. }
25... Nxb3 26. exf6 Qd6
{ White's rook faces an unpleasant choice. It can either leave the first rank unprotected or keep it under control, but then it has to go to a very passive position... }
27. Rc3
{ A blunder!   27.Rb1?!  g5∓  Black now tries to trade queens, as the endgame is nearly winning due to White's weak pawn on f6 which eventually will be lost.   27.Rc2  Qd3  28.Re2  Nd4∞  Keeping the position complicated, although it's definitely White who has to be very precise in order to keep the balance! }
27... Qd1
{ Black fails to find the refutation!   27...Qd4+!  Making use of the weak first rank.  28.Qe3   28.Qf2??  Qxf2+  29.Kxf2  Rd2+-+   28.Kh1  Qd2  29.Qb1   29.Qxd2  Rxd2-+  Threatening both mate and attacking the bishop.  Qd1+  30.Qxd1  Rxd1  Qd1+  29.Kf2  Qd2+  30.Kg3  Qxb2  31.Rxb3  Qxf6-+  With an extra pawn. On top of that, White also has a weak king... }
28. Re3 Qxe1+ 29. Rxe1 Rd2
{ The endgame is still better for Black, although it's a long way to go... }
30. Be5 g5 { Black wants to exploit the weakness of the f6-pawn. } 31. Re3
{ Black's knight wasn't doing much on b3, so why help it to get back into the game?   31.h4!?  gxh4   31...Kh7?  32.h5  Not allowing Black's king to approach the pawn.  32.Re4=  White will get the pawn back and might then try to create some threats against Black's king. }
31... Nd4 32. h4
{ 32.Bxd4  If one says A, he must continue with B! White could have gone for very drawish-looking rook endgame, even with the weak f6-pawn.  32...Rxd4  33.Rc3  33...Rd7  34.h4  gxh4  35.Rc4  Kh7  36.Rg4=  Black's king will never be able to reach g6. }
32... gxh4
{ 32...Nf5!  would win at least one pawn.  33.Rc3  White can try to activate his rook, but it's not at all dangerous for Black.  33...Nxh4  34.Rc8+  Kh7  35.Rf8  Kg6  36.Rg8+  Kf5-+ }
33. Re4
{ 33.Bxd4  Rxd4  34.Rc3  White lost some time, but the rook endgame is still holdable.  34...a5  35.b5  35...Kh7  36.Rc6  With big drawing chances. }
33... Nf5 { Now the position becomes very difficult to hold for White... } 34.
Rg4+ Kh7 35. b5
{ It's difficult to suggest anything better.   35.Rc4??  Rxg2+  36.Kxg2  Ne3+-+ }
35... Rd5 36. Bb8 Rxb5 37. Bxa7 Ra5
{ Eliminating the pawns on the queenside was not the most inspired decision, as it grants White some hope. He can try, for example, to trade some pawns and then sacrifice his bishop for the others, going for a drawn rook vs. rook and knight endgame.   37...Rb1+!  38.Kh2  h5  39.Re4  b5  White's king is in a mating net and Black should be able to slowly convert his extra pawn. }
38. Bxb6 Rxa3 39. Bf2
{ The time trouble must have been at fault ...   39.Kh2  would have been better, not allowing Black to play h3 and keeping the drawing chances. }
39... Ra1+
{ 39...h3!  40.gxh3  Rxf3-+  The f6-pawn is going to fall soon, too. } 40. Kh2
Ra2 41. Be1 { 41.Bxh4  h5  42.Rg5  Nxh4  43.Rxh5+  Kg6  44.Rxh4 } 41... Ra1 42.
Bc3 { 42.Bxh4  would have secured the draw.  42...h5  43.Rg5= } 42... Rc1 43.
Be5 Rc5 44. Re4 Kg6 45. f4
{ The final mistake... It was vital for the bishop to control the g3-square so that White's king is safe.   45.Rg4+  Kh7  46.Re4  Still hoping! }
45... Rc1 46. Rb4 h5 47. Rb8 Ng3 48. f5+ Kxf5 49. Bxg3 hxg3+ 50. Kxg3 Kxf6 51.
Kh4 Rc5 52. Rg8 Rf5
{ A game of many mistakes, but we can learn so much from it!   1. Don't lose time on unnecessary moves @@StartBracket@@14... h6@@EndBracket@@.   2. When in trouble, try to create imbalances.   3. Never create unnecessary weaknesses in your camp.   4. Keep in mind that rook endgames can save the day. We all know their drawish tendency, even when we're down material.   5. Don't forget about the king's safety, even in endgames! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Yuriy Kuzubov vs. Monika Socko Gibraltar 2018"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let's now enjoy another nice game by a strong female GM! } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2 Bb7 7. Bg5
{ As mentioned in the course, even though this move is the most popular one, it already seems to be an inaccuracy. It can't be good to move the same piece a couple of times in the opening, ignoring the development of other pieces! }
7... d6 8. e3 Nbd7
{ This doesn't change much and it will soon transpose to our line. 8...h6 is the move recommended in the course. }
9. Bh4 h6 10. Bd3
{ A rare move, although the response is very similar to the one examined in the course after  10.Be2  .   10.Nd2  is the only way to make sure both the h5- and e4-squares are covered.  See the 4.Nbd2 b6 5.a3 line for more. }
10... g5 11. Bg3 h5
{ White's bishop is now in big trouble: Black is planning to win it with h4. If  12.Nxg5  , then the bishop still doesn't get to escape after  12...h4  13.Bf4  e5  . }
12. h4 g4 13. Ng5 Bxg2 { Winning a pawn! } 14. Rg1 Bb7 15. Qa4
{ White wants to castle long and then try to attack Black's king. } 15... a6
16. Rc1 Ke7
{ A brave move, getting rid of the unpleasant pin, thus preventing c5. Black's king feels safe enough in the center!   16...Qe7  17.c5!  Making use of the pin.  17...dxc5  18.dxc5  bxc5  19.Qa5  Rc8  20.Ke2  White would have good compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
17. Qc2 Ne8 { Planning to push back White's most active piece. } 18. b4 f6
{ 18...c5  would have been more precise. } 19. Ne4
{ 19.c5!  A nice intermediate move which both players missed!  19...bxc5   19...fxg5  20.c6±  20.bxc5  dxc5  21.dxc5  Bc6  22.Be4  Keeping the position very unclear! }
19... c5
{ The opportunity to open up the position for the bishop pair is now gone. }
20. bxc5 bxc5 21. Rb1 Bc6 22. Nc3 cxd4 23. exd4 Rc8
{ Why not x-ray White's queen? } 24. Kd2 e5
{ While White should try to open up the position for his bishops, Black must do the exact opposite! The bishop is now unhappy on g3. }
25. Rge1 Kf8 26. c5
{ White goes all in!   26.d5  would have been better.  26...Ba8  27.f3∞  Black's bishop on a8 isn't a good piece either and White can try to open up some files on the kingside. }
26... dxc5 { 26...Qa5  d4 is hanging now.  27.Rb4  dxc5-+ } 27. d5 Bb5 28. Nxb5
{ 28.Bf5  Nd6  29.a4  would have kept the position tense, with chances for both sides. }
28... axb5
{ Another example where the pair of knights are better than the pair of bishops! }
29. Bxb5 Nd6
{ The knight is the best piece to block the advance of the passed pawn. } 30.
Bxd7 Qxd7
{ It becomes clear now that Black's knight on d6 is much, much better than White's poor bishop on g3. }
31. Rb6 Kf7 32. Bxe5 { Desperation. } 32... fxe5 33. Rxe5 Rce8
{ 33...Rh6-+  would secure the king and win the game much faster! } 34. Rxe8
Nxe8 35. Qg6+ Kf8 36. d6
{ 36.Re6  would make Black's life not so easy due to the very passive pieces.  36...Qf7!  The only move that keeps the winning chances!   36...Qxd5+?  37.Ke1  Qd7  38.Qf5+  Qf7  39.Qxc5+  Kg8  40.Qg5+  Kf8   40...Ng7??  41.Re7+-  41.Qc5+=  37.Qg5  Qxf2+  38.Kc1  Rh7∓ }
36... Rh7 { Probably time trouble...   36...Qf7-+ } 37. Rb8 Qf7 38. Qe4
{ 38.Qxf7+  Rxf7  39.Rd8!  The move missed by both GMs! White unexpectedly saves himself.  39...Rxf2+  40.Ke3  Rf7  41.d7  Re7+  42.Kf4  c4  43.dxe8=Q+  Rxe8  44.Rd5= }
38... Rh6 39. Kc1 Rxd6 40. Qe5 Qc4+
{ White will be mated shortly! A great example of how to play against the bishop pair. }
