[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Benjamin vs. Le Quang Liem, St. Louis 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Nd2 d5
{ In the course, we prefer to start with a different move order andcastle short before playing d5. The text move is not much different and will most likely transpose at some point. }
5. Bg2 O-O 6. Nf3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 { Now we get to theline with 4. Nbd2 b6 5.g3. }
8. b3 { White goes for a position with a double fianchetto. } 8... Nbd7 9. Bb2
Ne4
{ The game is following our analysis so far... Check the line to see what happens after 10. Nxe4. }
10. Rc1 f5 11. a3 Be7 12. b4 c6 { Consolidating the center. } 13. Qb3 Kh8
{ Prophylaxis. The king wasn't feeling safe on g8 with the white queen on b3. }
14. Rfd1 Qe8 { Black wants to start some counterplay on the kingside. } 15. Ne5
{ 15.b5?!  doesn't really compromise our pawn structure.  15...c5!   15.Ne1!?  It was probably better to keep as many pieces on the board as possible, as Black has less space.  15...Qh5  16.Nd3  Also, White's knight is much better placed on d3, as it controls the dark squares very well.  16...Bd6   16...Qxe2??  17.Nf3+-  And Black's queen is trapped!  17.e3  With a slightly better position for White. }
15... Nxe5 16. dxe5
{ This change of the pawn structure is more convenient for Black. } 16... Rd8
{ 16...c5!  Black needed to open up his bishop immediately!  17.Nxe4  dxe4  With a small edge for Black thanks to the possibility of attacking on the kingside with either f4 or h5-h4. }
17. cxd5 exd5
{ Black's bishop is a bit unhappy on b7 now. Black's strategy should involve solving this issue. }
18. e3 c5 19. bxc5 Bc6 { A fine intermediate move. } 20. Qa2 bxc5 21. f3 Ng5
{ 21...Nxd2  22.Rxd2  f4!  Black missed a nice opportunity to create a strong passed pawn in the center, while also opening up his light-squared bishop and burying White's.  23.exf4  d4∓ }
22. f4 Ne4 23. Nxe4 fxe4 24. Ba1
{ White tries to find a better square for his queen. } 24... Qg6 25. Qe2 Bb7
{ a6 is covered now. } 26. Bf1 Bc8
{ It is interesting to notice how this bishop, which initially had been placed on the rather bad b7-square, is now creating all sorts of trouble for White - first on the queenside and now on the kingside, too! }
27. Qg2 h5 28. Rb1
{ White fails to find any counterplay and makes a serious mistake.   28.Be2=+  Trying to hold the position and waiting for Black to show how he's going to break through. }
28... d4 29. exd4 cxd4
{ It turns out that the rook on c1 was covering the vital c5-square! } 30. Re1
{ 30.Bxd4??  Rxd4  31.Rxd4  Bc5-+ } 30... e3
{ In light of these two connected passed pawns, White's position is hopeless. }
31. Rbc1 d3 32. Rc6 d2 33. Rd1 Qh7 34. Rc7 Rd7 35. Qc6 Rxc7 36. Qxc7 Re8 37.
Bb5 Qe4 38. Bxe8 e2 { A visually pleasing final position! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Pavel Maletin vs.  Alexander Riazantsev, Vladivostok 2014"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6
{ The game is starting out with a Nimzo move order, but soon it's going to transpose. }
5. e3 O-O 6. Bd3 d5 7. O-O Bb7
{ And we are back to our lines! Check the Nimzo line for all of White's options in this position. }
8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne5
{ White chooses the most aggressive approach, preparing an attack on the kingside with f4 and Qf3. }
9... Bd6 10. f4 c5
{ The game follows our theory, or does our theory follow this game? Once again, notice how important it is in these lines to have the knight still on b8 so that it can jump to c6, from where it will put a lot of pressure on White's center. }
11. Bd2
{ White deviates now with this slow move.  11.g4  would be more interesting. Checkthis line to find out how Black would continue. }
11... Nc6 { The pawn is hanging now! } 12. Ne2 Ne7
{ Opening the diagonal for the bishop and preparing Ne4, although it is actually a loss of time.   12...Ne4!?  13.Bxe4  dxe4=  would be better. }
13. Ng3 Ne4 14. Bc3
{ White has managed to consolidate his center due to Black's slow play. } 14...
Nxc3 15. bxc3 Qc8
{ 15...g6!  was necessary!  16.f5  Bxe5  17.dxe5  Nc6  18.e6  Ne5  Even though the position looks dangerous, Black is fine, as the knight on e5 covers everything. }
16. Rc1
{ An unnecessary move.   16.Qh5  f5   16...g6??  is now a bad idea, as the queen comes to h6, turning the weak dark squares into a real problem.  17.Qh6  f5  18.h4+-  17.Ne2  Planning to continue the attack on the kingside with h3 and g4. It is unclear where Black's counterplay should take place, as White's center is very solid. }
16... c4 17. Bc2 f5
{ Black tries to close up everything on the kingside, with the intention of launching his counterplay on the queenside soon. }
18. a4 Bc6 19. Rb1 { That's why Rc1 was just a loss of time earlier. } 19...
Bd7 { The bishop will now keep an eye on the potential g4-breakthrough. } 20.
Qf3 { 20.Nxd7?  Qxd7=+  Black is basically playing with an extra pawn. } 20...
Be6 21. Ne2 Rb8 22. h3 { Preparing g4. } 22... a6
{ Black wants to play b5. Who's going to be faster? } 23. Kh1 b5 24. axb5 Rxb5
{ 24...axb5  would have been better, as White's 25.g4 is still premature.  25.g4  fxg4  26.Nxg4   26.hxg4  Bxe5  27.dxe5  Bxg4-+  Bf5=+ }
25. Rxb5
{ A mistake! Why help Black's pawn get back to business?   25.Ra1  Rb2  26.Rfc1+=  Once again, Black's play would be slower here... }
25... axb5 26. g4 fxg4 27. Nxg4
{ 27.hxg4?  Loses a pawn.  27...Bxe5  28.dxe5  Bxg4-+ } 27... Bf5 28. e4
{ Desperation.   28.Bxf5  Qxf5  29.Ne5=+  would be holdable. } 28... Bxe4 29.
Bxe4 dxe4 30. Qxe4 h5 31. Nf2
{ The knight is now forced to a sad passive position. } 31... Qf5 32. Ng3 Qd5
33. Qxd5+ Nxd5 { White can't hold on to everything. } 34. Nfe4 h4 35. Nxd6 hxg3
36. Rf3 b4 37. Nxc4 bxc3 38. Rxg3 c2
{ What conclusions can we draw out of this game?    1. Time is essential in these lines in which each side attacks on a different flank.   2. Don't improve your opponent's pawn structure unless you have no other option!   3. If the e5-square is not under Black's control, we mustn't hurry to develop our b8-knight to d7 too soon. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Ernst Gruenfeld vs.  Efim Bogoljubow, Breslau 1925"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ The name of this opening is a homage to the player who was first to play it in a high-level game: GM Efim Bogoljubow. }
4. Nbd2 O-O
{ In the course we follow a different approach with  4...b6  , but we must remember that the theory has evolved a lot since 1925 when this game was played! }
5. a3 Be7 6. e3
{ 6.e4!  The modern approach! White doesn't miss the chance to take space in the center.  6...d6  7.Be2  Nfd7  By playing this move instead of the 'normal' 7...Nbd7, Black intends to follow up with  8...e5 when after 9. d5, he will be ready to counterattack with f5 as soon as possible. The other knight will develop to a6, but only after first playing a5 to prevent White's c5-idea.  8.b4  8...e5  9.d5  a5  With a slightly better position for White thanks to the extra space. }
6... d5 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. O-O c5
{ An almost symmetrical position. White has played the extra a3-move, but it's unclear what good it does, as b4 is not possible anymore. }
9. Qe2 cxd4 10. exd4 b6
{ Bogoljubov decides to switch to a Panov-like structure and aims to create an isolated pawn for White @@StartBracket@@after, say, taking on c4@@EndBracket@@, which will be convenient for Black, as the knight on d2 is badly placed. It would be better placed on c3, from where it controls both d5 and e4 and doesn't get in the way of White's dark-squared bishop. }
11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nc4 Bb7 13. Bd2 Rc8
{ Both sides have finished the development. White's task is to start an attack on the kingside, while Black should do his best to liquidate to an endgame in which he'd be better thanks to his superior pawn structure. }
14. Nce5 Bf6 15. Qe4 g6 16. Qg4 Ne7
{ A standard move, defending the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@just in case@@EndBracket@@, opening up the diagonal for the b7-bishop and aiming for Nf5 at some point. White also has to mind the threat of 18...Nxe5, as the bishop on d3 is unprotected. }
17. Be4 Ba6
{ White's other bishop is suddenly x-rayed and he loses a pawn after  18.Rfe1  Bxe5  19.dxe5  Nxe5  20.Nxe5  Qxd2  . }
18. Qf4 { Desperation. } 18... Bxe5 19. dxe5 f5
{ Giving White a chance to get back into the game.   19...Bxf1!  was winning for Black.  20.Qh6  20...f6∓ }
20. Qh6
{ White wants to play 21. Ng5 with a mate threat on h7.   20.exf6!  Rxf6  21.Qe3  Bxf1  22.Rxf1  when White would have good compensation for the exchange due to the bishop pair and Black's weak e6-pawn. }
20... Re8
{ The easiest way to defend against White's idea. Now after  21.Ng5  Black has  21...Nf8  protecting h7. At the same time, White is losing material: the rook on f1 and the bishop on e4 are both hanging. }
21. Bg5 fxe4 { A piece is a piece! } 22. Bf6 Nf5
{ 22...Nxf6  followed by  23... Nf5 was also good enough. } 23. Qg5 Nxf6 24.
exf6 exf3 25. Rfd1 Nd4 { An inspiring win! } *

